const CASES = [
  {id:1,title:`Hair Care Brand — Declining Profits`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`FMCG`,problem:`Your client is a hair care products manufacturer that has been facing declining profits since starting operations two years ago. The company makes two products. Help identify the root cause and recommend a way forward.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a hair care products manufacturer that has been facing declining profits since starting operations two years ago. The company makes two products. Help identify the root cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Before I structure the analysis — does the client manufacture and sell both products directly, or is any part outsourced? What is the revenue split between the two products, and which geographies does it serve?`},{s:`I`,t:`The client is fully integrated and operates only in India. It makes a shampoo and a hair serum. The shampoo contributes roughly 75% of total revenue and the serum 25%. Both are under profitability pressure.`},{s:`C`,t:`Understood. Declining profits stem from either falling revenues or rising costs. Should I focus on revenues first?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes — focus on revenues. The cost structure has not changed materially.`},{s:`C`,t:`On the revenue side, I would first determine whether the overall category is growing or contracting, and whether we are losing share within a healthy market. Starting with the shampoo, which carries the greater weight — is the category growing?`},{s:`I`,t:`The shampoo category is growing nationally. The client is ranked fourth and has been losing market share.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since the market is healthy but we are losing share, the issue is likely in our own product or go-to-market. On the product side, I would examine functional attributes — lather, fragrance, efficacy for different hair types — and experiential factors like packaging and brand perception. Is there any customer feedback pointing to a specific gap?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. Customer research shows the shampoo formula is too mild for Indian hair types, which tend to be thicker and require stronger cleansing. The product was originally developed for a Southeast Asian formulation that does not translate well to Indian hair.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a product-market fit gap at the formulation level. Short term: bundle the shampoo with the serum to improve perceived value, and run targeted communication acknowledging the reformulation in progress. Medium term: reformulate with a stronger cleansing base suited to Indian hair profiles. Now on the serum — is it also a market share issue?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, but it is more recent. Focus on external demand-side factors.`},{s:`C`,t:`For external demand I look across four levers: affordability, availability, accessibility, and brand preference. What is driving the recent preference shift away from the serum?`},{s:`I`,t:`The serum's brand ambassador — a prominent Bollywood actor — recently became embroiled in a significant political controversy. Several consumer groups have called for a brand boycott, hurting serum sales.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is brand reputational contamination. Immediate action: terminate the ambassadorship and issue a neutral, product-focused statement. Shift all marketing to clinical efficacy claims — heat protection, frizz control — to reanchor the serum's identity around product performance rather than the ambassador's image. Longer term: diversify the ambassador portfolio across multiple personalities to avoid single-person concentration risk.`}]},
  {id:2,title:`Biscuit Retailer — Declining Profits`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Retail`,problem:`Our client is a well-known biscuit retailer based in Lucknow with shops in residential neighbourhoods. Over the last three months, the business has experienced a decline in profits. Help identify why.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a well-known biscuit retailer based in Lucknow with shops in residential neighbourhoods. For the past three months profits have been declining. Help identify why.`},{s:`C`,t:`I want to understand the business model first. Does the client manufacture the biscuits, or procure them from a manufacturer? How are they distributed to the shops, and who are the primary customers?`},{s:`I`,t:`The client procures biscuits from a manufacturer, stores them at a warehouse near the city, and supplies them to its own retail outlets. It sells a single variety of biscuits to middle-class families in the area. There are no significant local competitors.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since there are no new competitors and the client has a strong local reputation, I suspect the issue lies on the cost side rather than revenue. May I start there?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, start with costs.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will trace costs along the supply chain: procurement from the manufacturer, inbound transportation, warehousing and storage, and delivery to retail outlets. Has there been any change in the manufacturer's pricing or supply terms?`},{s:`I`,t:`No change. The client has worked with the same wholesaler for five to six years and terms have remained stable.`},{s:`C`,t:`What about transportation? The client uses its own trucks. Have fuel costs or routes changed?`},{s:`I`,t:`Fuel costs have risen, but this has affected the whole industry. It is not client-specific. Move on.`},{s:`C`,t:`Let me look at storage. The client has been using the same warehouse for eight years. I would split potential issues into two categories — human factors such as mishandling, pilferage, or poor inventory management like using LIFO for perishable stock, and environmental factors such as pest damage or weather-related spoilage. Has there been any change in the warehouse team or procedures recently?`},{s:`I`,t:`New warehouse staff joined six months ago without proper training, leading to poor stock rotation. But the bigger issue this monsoon season has been significant damage to biscuit packets from rodent infestation.`},{s:`C`,t:`That explains the cost increase. Recommendations: in the immediate term, deploy pest control, conduct an emergency stock inspection to remove damaged inventory, and retrain all warehouse staff on FIFO protocols. For the medium term, renovate the warehouse to make it rodent-proof and weather-resistant, and install CCTV monitoring to deter pilferage. Quarterly inventory audits would prevent a recurrence.`}]},
  {id:3,title:`NBFC — Declining Loan Sales`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`BFSI`,problem:`Your client is a Mumbai-based NBFC that has been experiencing a decline in loan sales over the past few months. Identify the root cause.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a Mumbai-based NBFC that has been experiencing a decline in loan sales over the past few months. Identify the root cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Before I dive in — is the decline specific to this client, or are competitor NBFCs also experiencing it? And does the client offer both retail and corporate loans?`},{s:`I`,t:`The client has operated from Mumbai since 2000 and offers both retail and corporate loans — both segments are affected. Competitors are not facing the same issue.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since it is client-specific, the problem is operational or commercial, not macroeconomic. Does the client distribute loans directly to customers, or also through intermediaries like DSEs — Direct Selling Executives?`},{s:`I`,t:`Both channels are used. DSEs are essentially loan brokers who submit applications on behalf of customers. The DSE channel has seen a significant decline.`},{s:`C`,t:`Let me understand the DSE workflow: the customer goes to the broker, the broker presents all available options including the client's products, the broker submits applications, the client reviews them, responds to the broker, and if approved, the deal is signed. Has the number of applications coming through DSEs fallen?`},{s:`I`,t:`Application volumes are stable. The product terms and interest rates are competitive. The drop is happening after applications are submitted.`},{s:`C`,t:`If applications are coming in at the same rate but conversions have dropped, and product pricing and broker commissions are competitive, the most likely bottleneck is our response time. A slow turnaround on credit decisions would cause brokers to steer customers toward lenders who respond faster.`},{s:`I`,t:`Exactly right. Competitors have invested in process automation and are converting customers significantly faster than we are.`},{s:`C`,t:`Recommendation: invest in digitising the credit assessment workflow to reduce internal decision time. Set a target of 24 to 48 hours for loan approval decisions. Assign a dedicated DSE relationship manager to proactively follow up with brokers on pending applications. Track DSE-level conversion rates weekly to identify where drop-offs occur. Speed of response is the key competitive lever here.`}]},
  {id:4,title:`Automotive Manufacturer — Declining Profits`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Automobiles`,problem:`Our client is a 50-60 year old automotive manufacturer that procures parts, assembles them, and sells finished vehicles across India. Profits have fallen by approximately 10% over the past year. Help identify the cause.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a 50-60 year old automotive manufacturer that procures parts, assembles, and sells vehicles across India. Profits have fallen by approximately 10% over the past year. Help identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Is the decline coming from lower revenues, higher costs, or both? And what is the product mix — passenger vehicles, commercial vehicles, or both?`},{s:`I`,t:`It is a cost issue. The client manufactures commercial vehicles, passenger vehicles, and spare parts — contributing roughly 50%, 45%, and 5% of revenues respectively. It has five assembly plants: one each in Pune, Kolkata, and Lucknow, and two in Chennai.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will trace costs along the value chain: raw material procurement, inbound logistics, manufacturing, warehousing, outbound distribution, and after-sales. Has there been any significant change in procurement recently?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The client recently changed its supplier base to consolidate sourcing closer to the two Chennai plants.`},{s:`C`,t:`That change would have two opposing cost effects: transportation costs for parts going from Chennai to the Pune, Kolkata, and Lucknow plants would increase, while raw material procurement costs may have fallen due to vendor consolidation. Do we have the numbers?`},{s:`I`,t:`Correct on both counts. Transportation cost as a percentage of total costs rose from 5% to 8%. Raw material costs fell by 17% from a base of 15% of total costs.`},{s:`C`,t:`The net impact: transportation increase of 3 percentage points, minus the raw material saving of 17% of 15% which is 2.55 percentage points — a net cost increase of approximately 0.45 percentage points. That alone does not explain a 10% profit decline. What other cost heads have changed?`},{s:`I`,t:`Inventory carrying costs have increased. Can you explain why?`},{s:`C`,t:`With parts sourced from Chennai and needed at plants in Pune, Kolkata, and Lucknow, parts are in transit longer. More inventory is tied up in the pipeline at any given time, increasing carrying costs. Are there also quality issues from the new suppliers driving higher servicing expenses?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The new suppliers deliver parts with a higher defect rate, increasing warranty claims and the cost of transporting spare parts to service centres.`},{s:`C`,t:`To summarise three cost drivers: first, higher inbound freight from supplier consolidation near Chennai. Second, higher inventory carrying costs due to longer in-transit periods. Third, elevated warranty and servicing costs from new suppliers with quality issues. Recommendations: negotiate quality SLAs with financial penalties on defect rates into new supplier contracts. Evaluate partial re-sourcing to vendors closer to non-Chennai plants to reduce freight costs. Build a regional buffer inventory near Pune and Lucknow to reduce in-transit dependency.`}]},
  {id:5,title:`IT Company — Cost Optimisation`,type:`Operations`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`IT & ITES`,problem:`Our client is a large Indian IT services company with 90% of its revenue from US clients, comparable to a Wipro or TCS. Management wants to reduce operating costs by 10% within two years. Help develop a strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a large Indian IT services company with 90% of revenue from US-based clients. Management wants to cut operating costs by 10% within two years. Help develop a strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`In IT services, employee cost is the dominant cost at roughly 55-65% of revenue. I will structure my approach around: first, employee costs, broken into team count, average cost per team, and headcount per team; and second, other operating costs including real estate, sales, and technology. Does that framing work?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. Start with employee costs.`},{s:`C`,t:`On bench utilisation: the proportion of employees not billed to active projects represents direct cost waste. Introducing dynamic staffing aligned to project lifecycle phases would reduce idle bench time. When a project approaches go-live it needs more people; during design phases fewer are required. Strict performance accountability for billed-but-low-contribution resources, supported by a project management tracking tool, would reduce this waste.`},{s:`I`,t:`What else within employee costs?`},{s:`C`,t:`The pyramid ratio — the mix of junior, mid, and senior employees. If technical requirements across junior and mid levels are comparable, tilting the pyramid toward a higher proportion of junior staff reduces average cost per person without compromising delivery. Additionally, the onshore-to-offshore ratio: US-based onshore employees cost significantly more. Reducing onshore headcount by one senior resource can be equivalent in cost savings to reducing 10 offshore resources.`},{s:`I`,t:`Any other factor for team composition?`},{s:`C`,t:`Within India, relocating certain roles to Tier-2 cities — Pune, Coimbatore, Jaipur — where cost of living and salary expectations are lower reduces costs for comparable skill levels. This works well for support functions and testing roles. For attrition reduction: offering project-completion-linked retention bonuses lowers costly mid-project turnover, which is expensive when accounting for recruitment, onboarding, and knowledge ramp-up time.`},{s:`I`,t:`What other operating cost areas would you explore beyond employee costs?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three areas: first, automation — increasing automated testing in quality assurance can reduce manual testing headcount and simultaneously improve delivery speed and quality. Second, real estate — review office space utilisation across all 15 cities and consolidate where occupancy rates are low; co-working arrangements work well for smaller city offices. Third, variable pay structure — shifting a larger portion of compensation to performance-linked variable pay creates a more flexible cost base that scales with business volumes.`}]},
  {id:6,title:`Global Investment Bank — India Entry Evaluation`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`BFSI`,problem:`A US-based global investment bank ranked in the top 20 worldwide wants to enter the Indian market. Help evaluate whether this is a viable opportunity and how they should approach it.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`A US-based global investment bank, top 20 globally, wants to enter the Indian market. Evaluate the opportunity and advise on the approach.`},{s:`C`,t:`I want to understand the bank's existing footprint first. What are its core product lines — ECM, DCM, M&A advisory, FX? And what has driven the decision to target India now?`},{s:`I`,t:`The bank's primary revenue drivers are M&A advisory, DCM, and FX. It serves Fortune 1000 companies, mid-sized multinationals, and high-net-worth individuals. The rationale is that its US and European core markets are slowing, while India's capital markets are growing rapidly.`},{s:`C`,t:`My evaluation framework covers four dimensions: macro attractiveness of India for investment banking, regulatory environment, competitive landscape, and financial viability. On macro: India's GDP growth above 7%, a rapidly expanding capital markets ecosystem, and increasing cross-border M&A activity make the backdrop attractive. On regulation: foreign banks can operate freely in investment banking in India. Is that correct?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, regulatory conditions are broadly open and supportive.`},{s:`C`,t:`On competition: global players like Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, and JPMorgan are already present in India. Domestic challengers like Kotak and Axis have strong corporate relationships. The bank's differentiation would need to come from its global M&A transaction network and cross-border DCM origination capability — bringing Indian companies to international capital markets and vice versa. Two additional factors I would assess: does the bank have any existing India client relationships or alumni networks that could provide early traction? And what mode of entry is preferred — greenfield, JV with a domestic player, or boutique acquisition?`},{s:`I`,t:`No existing India presence. Open to either direct setup or a local partnership. Can you estimate potential year-one revenue?`},{s:`C`,t:`Revenue estimate: three M&A deals at an average size of $5 billion with a 5% advisory fee gives $750 million. Four DCM deals at $2 billion with 3% margin gives $240 million. Ten ECM deals at $1 billion with 2% margin gives $200 million. Total year-one revenue: approximately $1.19 billion. This must be set against setup costs — office, staffing, regulatory licensing — typically $30-50 million in year one for a lean operation. The business is financially attractive if deal closure rates match assumptions.`},{s:`I`,t:`What is your recommendation on mode of entry?`},{s:`C`,t:`I would recommend entering via a joint venture with a well-connected domestic boutique or mid-tier bank to accelerate regulatory approvals and client relationship access. Focus initial coverage on M&A advisory and cross-border DCM, where the global network creates a clear differentiation advantage over domestic players. Target large Indian conglomerates with international expansion ambitions as anchor clients in year one.`}]},
  {id:7,title:`Multi-Brand Authorised Car Service Network — India Feasibility`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Automobiles`,problem:`A prominent Indian industrialist recently visited Scandinavia, where he observed a third-party authorised multi-brand car service model — independent workshops certified by multiple OEMs to service any car brand. He wants to evaluate whether a similar concept could work profitably in India.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`A prominent Indian industrialist has observed an authorised multi-brand car service model in Scandinavia. He wants to evaluate whether such a business can succeed in India — independent service workshops certified by multiple OEMs, competing with both dealer networks and local garages.`},{s:`C`,t:`My evaluation covers four areas: customer need-gap, supply-side feasibility, competitive positioning, and financial viability. On the customer side: what would bring a car owner to this service over their OEM dealer or a local garage?`},{s:`I`,t:`Customers want OEM-level service quality and warranty compatibility, at a lower cost than dealer rates, with faster turnaround.`},{s:`C`,t:`That defines the value proposition clearly. OEM dealer networks offer quality and warranty coverage but are expensive and slow. Local garages are cheap and fast but unreliable in quality. This multi-brand network occupies the middle — better than local garages, cheaper and faster than dealers. On the supply side: parts availability is the critical enabler. OEMs generate significant revenue from spare parts. Would they supply an independent network at competitive rates?`},{s:`I`,t:`OEMs would likely view this as a threat to their authorised dealer service revenue and charge higher prices for parts supplied to an independent network.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is the central commercial risk. Without competitive parts pricing our cost advantage over dealers collapses. We would need to negotiate preferential OEM supply agreements, or build relationships with quality-certified Tier-2 parts manufacturers making OEM-equivalent components. On labour — there is a large pool of trained mechanics in the unorganised sector, but cross-brand standardised training would be required. Is that feasible?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes — a training programme is feasible but would take six to nine months to build a certified workforce across brands.`},{s:`C`,t:`Recommendation: the concept is commercially viable given India's large and growing vehicle base. Three conditions for success: first, secure multi-brand parts supply agreements before launch. Second, build a proprietary technician training and certification programme. Third, pilot in two or three metro cities with high vehicle density — Pune or Ahmedabad are better test markets than Delhi where the unorganised sector is already sophisticated. Position clearly as a premium alternative to the unorganised sector, not a replacement for OEM dealerships.`}]},
  {id:8,title:`Pro Kabaddi Franchise — Southeast Asia Expansion`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Sports & Media`,problem:`Your client owns a successful Pro Kabaddi franchise in India. With the sport gaining international traction through global broadcast rights, the client wants to evaluate expanding into Southeast Asian markets — specifically Malaysia and Indonesia — to access broadcasting revenue, merchandise sales, and sponsorships. The next Southeast Asian Kabaddi Championship is eight months away. Help evaluate the decision.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client owns a successful Pro Kabaddi franchise and wants to enter the Southeast Asian market. Championship starts in eight months. Revenue targets: broadcasting rights, merchandise, sponsorships, and player development. Should they enter?`},{s:`C`,t:`I will structure this across four dimensions: country-level attractiveness, sport-specific industry dynamics in the target market, commercial opportunity sizing, and operational readiness. Starting with country-level: Malaysia and Indonesia have large South Asian diaspora communities for whom kabaddi has cultural resonance. Government sports promotion policies in both countries are generally open to international sporting events. Are there known regulatory barriers to foreign franchise participation?`},{s:`I`,t:`Assume the regulatory environment is open. Move to industry dynamics.`},{s:`C`,t:`On sport dynamics, I would examine: existing kabaddi infrastructure and fan base in the region; competing sports for audience and sponsorship — football, badminton, and esports are dominant there; and the availability of local players. What is the estimated engaged viewership for kabaddi in the target markets?`},{s:`I`,t:`Approximately 20% of the South Asian diaspora — roughly 4-5 lakh people — follow kabaddi actively. General population interest is emerging but still limited.`},{s:`C`,t:`That defines a niche but monetisable audience. Broadcasting revenue would come primarily from South Asian-focused satellite channels operating in the region. Merchandise revenue is modest initially. The bigger opportunity is building brand equity for future market expansion. One operational concern: the team trains on indoor clay courts in India. Southeast Asian facilities use different surfaces and have higher ambient humidity, which affects player conditioning. With eight months, adaptation is manageable.`},{s:`I`,t:`The team is willing to adapt. What is your overall recommendation?`},{s:`C`,t:`Recommend entering, with a realistic year-one commercial objective: brand establishment and broadcast deal signing, not profit. Revenue from merchandise and sponsorships builds over time as local fan base develops. Partner with a local sports events management company in Malaysia to manage venue, marketing, and local player scouting. Lock in broadcast rights with South Asian diaspora-focused channels as the first commercial priority — this is the anchor revenue for year one.`}]},
  {id:9,title:`Weight-Management Supplement — Pricing and Launch Decision`,type:`Pricing`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Pharmaceuticals`,problem:`A leading nutraceutical company has developed a patented once-daily weight-management supplement that clinically reduces food cravings and supports gradual fat loss. There is no comparable product in the Indian market. Help decide whether to launch and how to price it.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`A leading nutraceutical company has a patented weight-management supplement — first of its kind in India. Should they launch and how should it be priced?`},{s:`C`,t:`A few clarifying questions: Is this an OTC product or prescription-only? What is the recommended dosage and course length? And do we have manufacturing cost data?`},{s:`I`,t:`It is an OTC product — available without a prescription. Recommended course: 90 days, one capsule per day. Manufacturing cost data is not yet available. Management wants value-based pricing.`},{s:`C`,t:`Understood. I will evaluate three approaches — cost-based, substitute-based, and value-based — and triangulate. For value-based pricing, the consumer value comes from: reduced food expenditure, avoided future health costs from obesity-related conditions, and improved quality of life. Let me quantify the direct savings.`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, please quantify the consumer value.`},{s:`C`,t:`An overweight individual who overeats spends approximately Rs 150-200 extra per day on food beyond a healthy intake baseline. If the supplement helps reduce this by 25-30%, the savings are roughly Rs 45-55 per day, or approximately Rs 4,000-5,000 over the 90-day course. On health costs: obesity-related conditions — diabetes, hypertension, joint issues — each carry significant out-of-pocket treatment costs. Avoiding or delaying even one such condition could save Rs 20,000-50,000 over time.`},{s:`I`,t:`Can we cross-check against substitutes?`},{s:`C`,t:`Substitute-based check: gym memberships cost Rs 2,000-4,000 per month; structured diet programmes cost Rs 3,000-8,000 per month; other nutraceuticals cost Rs 500-1,500 per month but lack clinical validation. Our patented product with clinical evidence should command a premium over generic supplements. I recommend a launch price of Rs 2,799 for the 90-day course — approximately Rs 31 per capsule. This is affordable relative to substitute costs and positions the product as clinically differentiated.`},{s:`I`,t:`Should the company proceed with the launch?`},{s:`C`,t:`Yes. The product is patented with no direct competition and targets a large and growing market — India has over 135 million overweight adults. Launch should be led through pharmacy chains and wellness platforms like Apollo Pharmacy, 1mg, and PharmEasy. Dermatologists and endocrinologists are useful prescription influencers even for an OTC product. A clinical-trial-led marketing campaign differentiates this from the crowded, unproven supplement space.`}]},
  {id:10,title:`Ready-to-Drink Cold Brew Coffee — Go-to-Market Strategy`,type:`GTM Strategy`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`FMCG`,problem:`Our client is an established beverage manufacturer with 20 years in the Indian market, known for fruit juice and energy drink brands. It has developed a new ready-to-drink cold brew coffee range — four variants in 250 ml cans with a three-month shelf life. This is the first such product from an established Indian beverage company. Help take it to market.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a well-known Indian beverage manufacturer launching a new RTD cold brew coffee range — four variants, 250 ml cans, three-month shelf life. First of its kind from an established Indian brand. Develop a go-to-market strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`This is a first-mover product in the premium coffee segment. My GTM framework covers: target customer and positioning, pricing, distribution, and launch activation. On targeting: cold brew is an urban, premium, lifestyle beverage. The natural audience is urban professionals aged 22-38 who frequent cafes but want a convenient, ready-to-consume alternative. Is this aligned?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The client wants to capture premium urban consumers and maximise revenue quickly. What pricing do you recommend?`},{s:`C`,t:`Benchmarking: a café cold brew costs Rs 200-280; packaged imports cost Rs 150-200 in premium retail; energy drinks with comparable caffeine are priced Rs 80-120. Our product bridges the café experience and retail convenience. I recommend launching at Rs 129 per can — premium over energy drinks, accessible versus café prices, and a clean price point for impulse purchase.`},{s:`I`,t:`Agreed on pricing. What is your distribution strategy?`},{s:`C`,t:`Priority channels: first, modern trade — premium supermarkets like Nature's Basket, Foodhall, and DMart for the at-home occasion. Second, quick-commerce — Blinkit, Swiggy Instamart, and Zepto for on-demand impulse consumption; this is where cold brew's convenience proposition is strongest. Third, corporate cafeterias and co-working spaces — office workers are the primary audience and this channel enables bulk placement with minimal marketing spend. Avoid pushing into general neighbourhood stores at launch — the product needs a premium environment to establish its brand positioning first.`},{s:`I`,t:`How would you activate the launch?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three activation pillars: first, experiential sampling at high-footfall corporate areas — Cyber Hub Gurgaon, BKC Mumbai, Koramangala Bengaluru — where the target consumer is most concentrated. Second, digital campaign through Instagram and LinkedIn targeting working professionals; partner with productivity and lifestyle creators who speak authentically to this demographic. Third, leverage the client's existing trade relationships — the juice and energy drink distribution network already has shelf access with the same premium retail channels we are targeting, giving immediate route-to-market.`}]},
  {id:11,title:`Netflix India — Grow Market Share by 20% in One Year`,type:`Growth Strategy`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Media / OTT`,problem:`Netflix India currently holds approximately 25% market share in the subscription streaming category with two major competitors. The client wants to grow market share by 20 percentage points within one year. Help develop a strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Netflix India holds approximately 25% market share in subscription streaming. Two major competitors exist. The client wants to grow share by 20 percentage points in one year. Help develop a strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`Netflix in India primarily targets urban college students and young professionals, differentiates on original content quality, and is positioned as a premium platform. Current plans are Rs 500 for single-screen, Rs 650 for two screens, and Rs 800 for four screens. Is that accurate?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, that is correct.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will structure the growth strategy around two levers: product and pricing to attract new segments, and distribution and geographic expansion to reach underserved audiences. On product and pricing: the Rs 500 entry point is too high for many price-sensitive Indian consumers. Netflix should introduce a mobile-only plan at Rs 149-199 that provides full content access on a single mobile screen at lower resolution. This is a proven lever — Netflix deployed this globally with strong results.`},{s:`I`,t:`What is the risk of existing subscribers downgrading?`},{s:`C`,t:`Some downgrade risk exists, but it is manageable. Designing the mobile plan with meaningful limitations — mobile screen only, no downloads, lower resolution — makes it unappealing for existing subscribers on larger screens. The net benefit from new subscriber addition at lower ARPU will outweigh marginal revenue loss from downgrades, especially given India's massive mobile-first internet user base exceeding 750 million.`},{s:`I`,t:`Good. What other growth levers would you recommend?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three additional levers: first, regional content investment — significantly accelerate production of Tamil, Telugu, Malayalam, and Kannada originals where Amazon Prime Video and Disney Plus Hotstar have stronger libraries. Original regional content drives subscriptions among non-Hindi audiences who currently feel underserved. Second, telco bundling partnerships with Jio and Airtel to offer Netflix at discounted rates within data plans, unlocking Tier-2 city subscribers who may not pay separately but would accept it as part of a bundle. Third, a dedicated app or plug-in streaming device similar to a Firestick at Rs 999-1,499 targeting households with standard televisions but no smart TV capability — this hardware play unlocks 60-80 million additional households.`}]},
  {id:12,title:`Cement Manufacturer — Growth and Margin Improvement Strategy`,type:`Growth Strategy`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Cement`,problem:`Our client is a promoter-driven cement company that has operated in India for 30-40 years. The industry is growing at 14% per annum but the client grows at only 12%. The client's EBITDA margin is also 2 percentage points below industry average. Devise a strategy to improve both.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is an established Indian cement manufacturer growing at 12% while the industry grows at 14%, and earning margins 2 percentage points below the industry average. Devise a strategy to improve both.`},{s:`C`,t:`Let me confirm the problem: the client is losing market share year-on-year and is less profitable per tonne than peers. Before recommending, I want to understand the product portfolio and geographic footprint. What grades does the client primarily produce?`},{s:`I`,t:`The client primarily produces OPC grades. I do not have more detail. Work with what is available.`},{s:`C`,t:`Understood. I will structure the strategy across revenue growth and margin improvement. For revenue growth, the key levers are product mix, distribution reach, and marketing effectiveness. On product mix: the industry growth is being driven heavily by infrastructure and housing construction, which increasingly prefers blended cements — PPC and PSC — for cost and performance reasons. Transitioning a portion of production to blended grades would help the client grow faster while simultaneously improving margins, as blended cements use less clinker per tonne of output, reducing fuel and raw material costs.`},{s:`I`,t:`That is useful. What else on the growth side?`},{s:`C`,t:`On distribution: the client should identify geographic markets where demand is growing faster than supply — typically Eastern India and Tier-2 city catchments in Central India — and expand dealer networks there. Each new geography accessed with existing production capacity is accretive at the margin. On marketing: cement is heavily influenced by contractor and mason recommendations at the site level. A structured mason loyalty programme — offering points redeemable for tools, training, or cash — is a proven lever for building brand preference at the point of specification.`},{s:`I`,t:`Now address the margin gap.`},{s:`C`,t:`The 2-percentage-point margin gap is most commonly driven by higher freight costs per tonne relative to peers, lower capacity utilisation, or an unfavourable product mix. On freight: the client should optimise logistics routing by increasing the share of rail transport, which is 20-30% cheaper than road for medium to long distances. Setting up additional grinding units closer to high-demand clusters reduces lead distance and freight spend. On product mix: shifting toward blended and premium grades, as mentioned, simultaneously grows revenue and reduces fuel cost per tonne. Both should close the margin gap within 18-24 months.`}]},
  {id:13,title:`PE Firm — Restaurant Chain Investment Due Diligence`,type:`Due Diligence`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Hospitality`,problem:`Your client is a PE firm considering taking a stake in a six-restaurant chain serving Spanish and Italian quick-service cuisine in metro and Tier-1 Indian cities. The chain is five years old, adding one city per year. The PE firm targets 30% growth on investment and plans to exit in four to five years. Evaluate whether to invest.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a PE firm evaluating a stake in a six-outlet quick-service restaurant chain serving Spanish and Italian cuisine in metro and Tier-1 cities. The chain is five years old. Target return: 30% growth. Exit horizon: four to five years. Should they invest?`},{s:`C`,t:`I will structure the evaluation across three pillars: market attractiveness, business-specific due diligence, and risk assessment. On market attractiveness: demand for international cuisine in urban India has grown substantially, driven by rising incomes, exposure through travel and social media, and increasing willingness to experiment with new cuisines. Only four to five players currently offer authentic Spanish and Italian cuisine in these cities. Is pricing comparable across them?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, all competitors operate at similar price points in the premium quick-service segment.`},{s:`C`,t:`Then the chain is competing on cuisine quality and dining experience rather than price. The target customer is a middle-to-high-income urban professional. To size the addressable market: in a metro city of two crore population, approximately 20% — 40 lakh people — fall in the income bracket that would visit this type of restaurant. A rough estimate of monthly revenue potential per location can be derived from average covers per day, average ticket size, and occupancy assumptions. What is the average ticket size per customer?`},{s:`I`,t:`Approximately Rs 400-500 per person, including food and beverages.`},{s:`C`,t:`At Rs 450 average ticket, 60 covers per day, and a 60-cover restaurant operating six days a week, monthly revenue per outlet would be approximately Rs 10-12 lakh. Across six outlets, annualised revenue is roughly Rs 7-8 crore. That is a small base for PE-level returns. Growth over five years through new outlet additions and revenue per outlet improvement is what drives the return. What risks concern the PE firm most?`},{s:`I`,t:`The firm is focused on competitive threats and financial sustainability of individual outlets.`},{s:`C`,t:`Three key risks: first, food delivery disruption — Zomato and Swiggy have trained customers to order restaurant-quality food at home. Spanish and Italian cuisines do not travel as well as Indian food, limiting delivery revenue potential. Second, dietary preference shifts among urban millennials toward healthy and plant-based eating. Third, location dependency — quick-service restaurant revenue is closely tied to footfall at the specific location. A landlord not renewing a lease for a profitable outlet is a material risk. For due diligence, I would review store-level P&Ls, revenue trends per location, lease terms and renewal rights, and the management team's capacity to open and operate additional locations. If unit economics show minimum Rs 2-3 lakh EBITDA per outlet per month and the core team is solid, the investment is worth pursuing.`}]},
  {id:14,title:`Low-Cost Airline — Turnaround Time Increase at Mumbai Airport`,type:`Operations`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Aviation`,problem:`Our client is a low-cost domestic airline carrier. Over the past three months, aircraft turnaround time at Mumbai airport has increased from 30 minutes to 45 minutes. The airline operates 10 aircraft at Mumbai exclusively on domestic routes. The issue is specific to this airline and this airport. Identify the cause.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a low-cost domestic airline. TAT at Mumbai airport has increased from 30 to 45 minutes over three months. 10 aircraft, domestic routes only, Mumbai-specific and airline-specific. Identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`TAT is the total time from wheels-down to next takeoff. I will trace every step: landing and taxi to the gate, passenger deplaning, baggage offloading, aircraft cleaning, fuelling, boarding, and pushback plus taxi to runway. Have any post-landing steps changed — deplaning, baggage offloading, or cleaning?`},{s:`I`,t:`Deplaning is unchanged. Baggage offloading is unchanged. Cleaning time and ground staff headcount are stable.`},{s:`C`,t:`That rules out gate-level process changes. Let me focus on the taxi phases — arrival taxi from the runway to the gate, and departure taxi from the gate to the runway. Has anything changed in the aircraft's allocated gate or the taxi routing it receives after landing?`},{s:`I`,t:`Good direction. The airline has been assigned a different terminal at Mumbai airport over the past three months.`},{s:`C`,t:`A new terminal assignment changes the physical distance the aircraft must taxi. If the new terminal is farther from the main runway in use, inbound taxi time increases. At a typical ground speed of 20-25 km/h on taxiways, each extra kilometre of taxi adds approximately 2.5-3 minutes. How far is the new terminal from the primary runway compared to the old one?`},{s:`I`,t:`The new terminal is approximately 2 km farther from the main runway. However, boarding at the new terminal saves about 4 minutes because passengers walk a shorter distance from the gate to the aircraft.`},{s:`C`,t:`Let me calculate the net impact: additional inbound taxi: 2 km at 20 km/h = 6 minutes. Additional outbound taxi: another 6 minutes. Total additional taxi time: 12 minutes. Boarding saving: minus 4 minutes. Net so far: 8 minutes increase. That does not fully explain the 15-minute TAT increase. Is there any congestion on the taxiway routing to the new terminal?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes — there is a shared taxiway near the new terminal that regularly sees holding time of 7-8 minutes during peak hours.`},{s:`C`,t:`That accounts for the remainder. Root cause: the new terminal assignment adds 8 minutes in taxi distance, plus 7 minutes average peak-hour taxiway holding — totalling the 15-minute TAT increase. Recommendation: negotiate with Mumbai airport authority for a priority taxi routing during peak operations, or seek partial reversion to the old terminal for peak-period slots. In the near term, revise all minimum turnaround schedule buffers to account for the new baseline TAT.`}]},
  {id:15,title:`Port Authority — Low Share in Regional Ship Repair Market`,type:`Operations`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Shipping`,problem:`Your client is a port authority operating a ship repair facility on India's eastern coast. Despite being strategically located on major Bay of Bengal shipping routes, the facility captures less than 2% of the regional ship repair market. Primary competitors are facilities in Malaysia and Singapore. Help identify why and suggest improvements.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a port authority with a ship repair facility on India's eastern coast. It captures less than 2% of regional market share. Primary competition: Malaysia and Singapore. Identify why and suggest improvements.`},{s:`C`,t:`What is the most important selection criterion for ship operators when choosing a repair facility, and how does this facility compare to competitors on that dimension?`},{s:`I`,t:`Turnaround time is the critical factor. The facility currently takes four to six days longer than Malaysian and Singaporean competitors for comparable repair scopes. Distance from the shipping route and price are secondary considerations.`},{s:`C`,t:`A four to six day delay is materially costly for ship operators given daily vessel operating costs and scheduling commitments. I would examine where in the repair process the time lag originates. Is the delay in administrative procedures — port clearance, documentation, crew immigration — or in the actual technical repair work?`},{s:`I`,t:`Both contribute. Port entry documentation for vessels takes significantly longer than at competing facilities. And while individual workers are skilled, process inconsistency leads to rework and re-inspection that extends turnaround time.`},{s:`C`,t:`On documentation: if processed digitally, the bottleneck is likely in multi-department approval layers. What is the typical elapsed time for a vessel to receive clearance to enter the repair berth?`},{s:`I`,t:`Vessel entry documentation takes two to three days here. In Malaysia this is completed within six to twelve hours.`},{s:`C`,t:`Recommendation on documentation: implement a single-window port clearance system — consolidating vessel entry, crew immigration, and repair documentation into one department with a 24-hour SLA. India has already built this capability for cargo imports through ICEGATE. Extending the same architecture to ship repair is operationally feasible. On workforce: what is causing the process inconsistency?`},{s:`I`,t:`There are no standardised repair protocols. Individual workers are capable, but different teams approach the same repair tasks differently, creating variability in output quality and time.`},{s:`C`,t:`Recommendations: introduce standardised repair protocols for the most common repair categories — hull maintenance, engine servicing, electrical systems — and certify all technicians against these standards. Adopt ISO 3834 quality standards for welding work, which is expected by international ship owners. Invest in semi-automated equipment for high-volume repetitive tasks to reduce human variability. On commercial positioning: once turnaround time improves, India's labour cost advantage over Malaysia and Singapore becomes a compelling selling point — price-competitive services with improved SLAs should be the primary market message.`}]},
  {id:16,title:`Metropolitan Government — Reducing Traffic Congestion by 20%`,type:`Unconventional`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Government / Public Sector`,problem:`Your client is the government of a large South Asian metropolitan city with a population of 15 million. Traffic congestion has reached critical levels, affecting productivity, air quality, and quality of life. The government wants to reduce vehicle density on key corridors by 20% within three years. Develop a strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`A large South Asian metropolitan government wants to reduce vehicle density on key corridors by 20% over three years. Population: 15 million. Mix of 6-lane arterial and 2-lane residential roads, approximately 80% concretised. Develop a strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will structure the strategy around four stakeholder groups: citizens and commuters, city infrastructure authorities, law enforcement, and private transport operators. What is the current modal split between private vehicles and public transport?`},{s:`I`,t:`Approximately 65% of daily trips are by private vehicle; only 30% use public transport.`},{s:`C`,t:`A 65% private vehicle share is the primary driver of congestion. Shifting even 10 percentage points to public transport would materially reduce corridor density. For public transport: increase bus frequency on the top 20 high-density corridors from every 15 minutes to every 5-7 minutes during peak hours. Extend metro coverage to the three highest-congestion suburbs where the density justifies it. Introduce air-conditioned express bus services for the working professional segment — this group currently defaults to private cars because public transport is perceived as uncomfortable and unpredictable.`},{s:`I`,t:`What demand-management measures would you recommend for private vehicles?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three measures: first, peak-hour parking pricing in the central business district — Rs 50-100 per hour from 8-10 am and 5-8 pm. Research consistently shows this is the single most effective congestion-reducing intervention for CBDs globally. Second, regulate app-based cab aggregators by limiting non-shared ride permits per zone per hour during peak periods — this addresses a rapidly growing source of CBD vehicle density. Third, coordinate with major corporate employers to stagger office discharge times across a two-hour window rather than a single 6 pm peak — this flattens the evening rush without requiring any infrastructure investment.`},{s:`I`,t:`What infrastructure improvements are achievable within three years?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three executable infrastructure investments: first, upgrade traffic signal systems to AI-driven adaptive control at the top 200 junctions — this improves throughput by 15-20% and implementation takes 12-18 months. Second, create dedicated bus-only lanes on three high-frequency arterial corridors. Third, redesign the ten worst bottleneck intersections with protected right-turn phases and pedestrian islands to eliminate the manual traffic police dependency at those junctions. On enforcement: deploy automated speed and traffic violation cameras at 50 key junctions, and introduce financial penalties for road contractors who exceed project timelines — construction zones are consistently among the highest contributors to peak congestion.`}]},
  {id:17,title:`Five-Star Hotel Mumbai — Declining Profitability`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Hospitality`,problem:`Your client is a standalone 5-star luxury hotel in Mumbai. It has been experiencing declining profitability for three years, with the decline accelerating in the last 12 months. The problem is specific to this hotel — competitors in the city are not affected. Help identify the root cause.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a standalone 5-star hotel in Mumbai experiencing declining profitability for three years. Issue is hotel-specific. Start with revenues.`},{s:`C`,t:`The hotel's revenue streams include rooms, restaurants, banquets, and ancillary services. Is the decline spread across all streams, or concentrated in one?`},{s:`I`,t:`Start with room revenue. That is where the pressure is most significant.`},{s:`C`,t:`Room revenue is driven by three factors: number of rooms, average daily rate, and occupancy. Has any of these changed materially?`},{s:`I`,t:`Number of rooms and average daily rate have not changed. Occupancy has remained high overall. Yet room revenue has declined.`},{s:`C`,t:`If all three direct drivers are stable but revenue has fallen, the issue must be in the mix of customers or the realisation per room. Specifically: has there been a shift from leisure tourists — who typically pay full rack rates — to corporate clients, who book at pre-negotiated corporate tariffs at a discount?`},{s:`I`,t:`Exactly right. Three years ago the tourist-to-corporate guest split was 50-50. Today it has shifted to 30-70. Corporate guests are contracted at rates significantly below what leisure travellers would pay.`},{s:`C`,t:`That explains the room revenue decline. The average effective rate per room has fallen as the higher-paying leisure segment has been replaced by lower-contracted corporate bookings. Recommendations: invest in marketing directly to the leisure and premium traveller segment — through luxury travel agencies, wedding planners for destination events, and premium OTA platforms. Create exclusive seasonal packages for leisure travellers that justify full rack rate. Also review the corporate rate structure — if corporate demand has grown significantly, renegotiating contracts upward at renewal is appropriate. Now, is there also an issue in the F&B segment?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The Continental restaurant has seen declining revenue. The Asian restaurant is performing normally.`},{s:`C`,t:`For the Continental restaurant, a key question is whether the decline is in covers or in revenue per cover. Has any analysis been done on payment patterns?`},{s:`I`,t:`There is a revenue leak from digital payment cashback and discount offers that effectively reduce what the hotel receives per transaction net of payment processor fees and cashback arrangements.`},{s:`C`,t:`Recommendation: renegotiate payment processor agreements to reduce merchant discount rates, particularly on premium cards. Consider offering loyalty points or hotel benefits as an incentive for preferred payment methods rather than accepting third-party cashback schemes that erode the hotel's net revenue per transaction.`}]},
  {id:18,title:`Car Insurance Company — Declining Profits`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Insurance`,problem:`Your client is a car insurance company experiencing a decline in profits. The problem is specific to the client — competitors are not affected. Revenues have remained stable. Identify the root cause and suggest recommendations.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a car insurance company with declining profits. Problem is client-specific. Revenues are stable. Identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since revenues are stable, the issue is on the cost side. For a car insurer, the dominant cost is claims payout. Has claims expenditure increased?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, claims payout has increased significantly.`},{s:`C`,t:`Claims cost can be decomposed as: number of claims times average payout per claim. Which has changed?`},{s:`I`,t:`The number of claims has increased. Average payout per claim is unchanged.`},{s:`C`,t:`Higher claims frequency points to a portfolio risk issue — the customer base has shifted toward higher-risk policyholders, or accident rates have genuinely increased for the existing customer base. Has the underwriting algorithm changed?`},{s:`I`,t:`No, the underwriting model has not been updated.`},{s:`C`,t:`Then the problem is in portfolio composition. I would segment policyholders by age group, vehicle type, geography, and income bracket. Young drivers under 25 have statistically higher accident frequencies. Has the proportion of young customers grown?`},{s:`I`,t:`Correct. The proportion of under-25 policyholders has grown, and this group has been involved in more accidents due to reckless driving behaviour.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a portfolio concentration risk in a high-frequency-claims cohort. Two recommendations: first, in the short term, revise premiums for the under-25 segment to reflect the actuarial risk differential — this restores underwriting profitability on new policies. Alternatively, introduce telematics-based pricing where young drivers can earn lower premiums by demonstrating safe driving through an in-app tracker, which also incentivises better behaviour. Second, in the medium term, actively diversify the portfolio by acquiring lower-risk customer segments: middle-aged professional drivers, corporate fleet accounts, and geographies with historically lower claim rates. This reduces concentration risk and improves the overall combined ratio.`}]},
  {id:19,title:`Agricultural Equipment Insurance Provider — Declining Revenues`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Insurance`,problem:`Your client is a pan-India insurance provider specialising in agricultural equipment insurance. It has been experiencing declining revenues for the past year, and this is broadly an industry-wide phenomenon. Help identify the root cause and suggest a way forward.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a pan-India agricultural equipment insurance provider facing declining revenues for the past year. This is an industry-wide issue. Help identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since this is industry-wide, the cause is structural or macroeconomic rather than a client-specific issue. Is the revenue decline from fewer active policies or lower premiums per policy?`},{s:`I`,t:`The number of active policies has fallen. Premium rates are unchanged.`},{s:`C`,t:`Fewer policies means fewer equipment purchases are being insured. Agricultural equipment insurance is typically linked to financing — when a farmer buys equipment on loan, the lender mandates insurance. Has there been a disruption in equipment purchase volumes?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. Two consecutive below-normal monsoon seasons have significantly reduced farm income. Farmers across major agricultural states have deferred large capital equipment purchases as a result, directly reducing new insurance policy origination.`},{s:`C`,t:`That confirms the mechanism: a macro agricultural stress event has suppressed equipment purchases, reducing insurance policy volume. This is an exogenous demand constraint the insurer cannot change directly. What are the client's options for stabilising revenues?`},{s:`I`,t:`Please suggest strategies the client can control.`},{s:`C`,t:`Three directions: first, cross-sell adjacent products to the existing equipment insurance customer base — crop insurance, farm storage and shed cover, and farm health insurance — to increase revenue per relationship and reduce dependence on equipment policy volume alone. Second, partner with equipment OEMs like Mahindra, TAFE, and Escorts to embed insurance as a package at the point of purchase, reducing dependence on loan-linked mandates. Third, develop a micro-insurance product for small and marginal farmers who own lower-value equipment like power tillers and hand tractors — this segment is currently underserved and less sensitive to large-scale macroeconomic cycles.`}]},
  {id:20,title:`Soft Drink Manufacturer — Volume Decline in Western European Markets`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`FMCG`,problem:`Your client is a multinational soft drink manufacturer with brands across global markets, including a strong presence in Western Europe. It has been experiencing declining profits for two to three years, driven by falling volumes. This is broadly an industry-wide issue in Western Europe. Help identify the cause and suggest recommendations.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a multinational soft drink manufacturer facing declining profits in Western Europe for 2-3 years. Revenue is falling because volumes have dropped. Costs and product mix are stable. People are simply drinking fewer carbonated soft drinks. This is industry-wide. Help.`},{s:`C`,t:`If volumes are falling industry-wide with stable pricing and costs, this is a structural demand-side shift, not a competitive issue. In Western Europe, several macro trends have been headwinds for carbonated soft drinks: sugar taxes in the UK, France, and Ireland; rising health consciousness among consumers under 40; and strong growth of substitutes — sparkling water, kombucha, and functional beverages. Is a combination of these driving the decline?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes — particularly the sugar tax and health consciousness among Gen Z and millennials, who are actively reducing sugar intake.`},{s:`C`,t:`This is a structural headwind requiring portfolio transformation. Two parallel tracks: defend the existing portfolio and build into growing categories. On defending: launch low-sugar and zero-sugar variants of all flagship brands — the Coca-Cola Zero and Pepsi Max precedent shows this can hold market share without damaging brand equity. Reformulate using stevia or monk fruit-based sweeteners to address ingredient-level health concerns.`},{s:`I`,t:`What about entering adjacent categories?`},{s:`C`,t:`Premium sparkling water enriched with minerals or electrolytes is the fastest-growing hydration category in Europe. The client's existing production infrastructure, cold chain distribution, and retail shelf relationships give it a strong advantage in launching a premium sparkling water range under a new sub-brand. Functional beverages — adaptogen-infused drinks, probiotic beverages, and kombucha — are adjacent opportunities, best accessed through acquisition of established challenger brands rather than building from scratch.`},{s:`I`,t:`What about markets outside Europe?`},{s:`C`,t:`Geographic rebalancing is an important parallel strategy. Soft drink consumption in South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Middle East, and Sub-Saharan Africa is growing at 6-10% per year as urbanisation and rising incomes drive category adoption — without the European health-consciousness dynamic yet. Reallocating marketing investment toward these high-growth markets while managing Europe as a stable, margin-focused portfolio is the right long-term balance.`}]},
  {id:21,title:`Neighbourhood Grocery Store — Declining Profits`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Retail`,problem:`Your client is a well-established neighbourhood grocery store owner whose business has been experiencing a decline in profits for the past five to six months. Identify the root cause.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a neighbourhood grocery store owner experiencing declining profits for five to six months. Help identify why.`},{s:`C`,t:`Is the decline from falling revenues, rising costs, or both? And has customer footfall changed, or has average spend per visit dropped?`},{s:`I`,t:`Revenue has fallen. Customer traffic appears consistent but spending per visit has dropped significantly. Costs are stable.`},{s:`C`,t:`Lower spend with stable footfall usually means basket-splitting — customers are buying some items here but redirecting larger purchases elsewhere. Let me trace the customer journey. Have any new competitors or alternative options appeared nearby recently?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. A mid-sized organised grocery chain opened a nearby outlet two months ago. They have launched an introductory promotion offering a 12% discount on purchases above Rs 800. Customers in this locality typically do monthly restocking, and their bills frequently exceed that threshold.`},{s:`C`,t:`That explains the behaviour precisely. Customers are redirecting their larger monthly restocking purchases to the chain to capture the discount, while continuing to visit our client for smaller daily needs where the Rs 800 threshold does not apply. This is basket-splitting triggered by a competitor promotion.`},{s:`I`,t:`What would you recommend?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three actions: first, introduce a customer retention offer — a monthly loyalty cashback of Rs 100 for cumulative purchases above Rs 2,000 in a month. This rewards regulars without requiring a per-transaction discount and does not sacrifice margin on every sale. Second, differentiate on assortment: stock categories the organised chain does not carry well — fresh local produce, regional specialty items, bakery products — to give customers a reason to prioritise this store for daily and weekly needs. Third, offer a credit account for trusted regular customers through an informal monthly arrangement. This creates stickiness and makes it inconvenient to redirect the full monthly spend to a competitor.`}]},
  {id:22,title:`Heritage Museum — Losing Visitor Share to New City Attractions`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Travel & Tourism`,problem:`Your client is a heritage museum in a historic European port city. Profits have declined 15% over the past year. The museum itself is unchanged. The city's overall tourist arrivals have increased. Visitor numbers to the museum have fallen. Identify the cause and recommend solutions.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a heritage museum in a historic European port city. Profits down 15% in the past year. Museum is unchanged internally. City tourism is growing. But museum visitors have fallen. Identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`If city tourism is growing but this museum is losing visitors, the museum is getting a smaller share of tourist time. Has the competitive landscape changed — new attractions opened or existing ones significantly upgraded?`},{s:`I`,t:`No new major museums. However, the city recently completed a major waterfront regeneration — a revamped harbour promenade with outdoor art installations, markets, and open-air performances, all free to visit.`},{s:`C`,t:`Those free waterfront experiences are competing directly for tourist time. A visitor choosing between a ticketed museum and a high-quality free harbour experience is increasingly choosing the outdoor option. A secondary question: has the museum's digital discoverability kept pace? Younger tourists research heavily on Google, TripAdvisor, and Instagram before visiting.`},{s:`I`,t:`The museum has very limited social media presence and has not updated its TripAdvisor listing in three years. The waterfront project has been actively promoted on social media by the city's tourism board and has significant traction.`},{s:`C`,t:`This is a two-part problem: the museum is being out-competed on experience appeal and out-marketed on digital discoverability. Recommendations: first, digital catch-up — update Google Business profile and TripAdvisor with high-quality photography, create monthly Instagram content showcasing the most visually striking exhibits, and ensure accurate opening hours and ticketing information are everywhere online. Second, differentiate on depth of experience — introduce AR-enhanced exhibit exploration, guided storytelling tours, and exclusive evening events that free outdoor venues cannot replicate. Third, collaborate rather than compete: partner with waterfront management to include a museum visit in recommended city itineraries, and place promotional materials at harbour visitor information points to convert waterfront visitors into museum visitors.`}]},
  {id:23,title:`Thermal Power Plant — Rising Coal Costs and Declining Profits`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Power`,problem:`Your client is a coal-based thermal power plant in Central India whose profits have been declining despite stable revenue under a long-term power purchase agreement. Help identify the cause and suggest improvements.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a coal-based thermal power plant in Central India. Revenue under its PPA is stable. Profits are declining. Help identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`If PPA revenue is fixed but profits are falling, the problem is cost-side. For a thermal plant, coal is typically 40-50% of generation cost and the primary variable expense. Has coal procurement cost increased?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. Coal costs have risen sharply over the past year.`},{s:`C`,t:`Coal costs can rise due to higher market prices, lower quality coal requiring greater volume per unit of energy, or a shift from regulated FSA coal to more expensive e-auction procurement. Plants in Central India typically hold Fuel Supply Agreements with Coal India at regulated prices. Has FSA supply been sufficient?`},{s:`I`,t:`FSA supply has been consistently below contracted volumes for the past year. Approximately 30% of coal needs have been met through e-auction channels.`},{s:`C`,t:`E-auction coal is typically priced 30-50% above FSA coal. At 30% of procurement through e-auction, this creates a meaningful weighted average fuel cost increase. Three recommendations: first, formally escalate to Coal India through the Ministry of Power to restore FSA supply to contracted levels — this is a regulatory track requiring senior management involvement. Second, evaluate blending FSA coal with imported coal from Indonesia or Australia to optimise cost per unit of energy compared to relying solely on e-auction domestic coal. Third, improve the plant's Heat Rate through targeted maintenance — cleaning heat exchangers, optimising combustion air ratios, and calibrating turbine clearances. A 2% improvement in Heat Rate reduces coal consumption by 2% at every output level.`}]},
  {id:24,title:`Bike Taxi App — Delhi-NCR Launch Strategy`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Transport`,problem:`Your client is an established cab hailing application that has built a new bike taxi product for Delhi-NCR. They need an end-to-end launch strategy including pricing, target geography, and implementation plan.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a cab hailing app with a new bike taxi product for Delhi-NCR. Regulatory approval is in place. Develop a launch strategy including target segment, pricing, and implementation.`},{s:`C`,t:`Before designing the strategy, I want to confirm the target use case. Is this primarily aimed at solving the first-and-last-mile connectivity problem around metro stations, or broader intra-city commuting?`},{s:`I`,t:`The primary use case is metro connectivity — specifically addressing the last-mile gap for office commuters in Gurgaon, which has strong metro coverage and dense corporate presence.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a well-defined and high-frequency use case. The value proposition versus auto-rickshaws is speed, predictable pricing through the app, and convenience. On pricing: what economics does the client need the model to support on the driver side?`},{s:`I`,t:`Drivers expect approximately Rs 20,000 per month in net income, after paying EMI for the bike. The major costs are R&D, fuel, and driver earnings. No margin is targeted initially.`},{s:`C`,t:`At Rs 20 per km and assuming 50 km of billable distance per day across 25 working days, a driver earns Rs 25,000 gross per month. After the platform takes a 20% commission, the driver nets Rs 20,000 — in line with expectations. However, at Rs 20 per km, we are pricing above auto-rickshaws at Rs 15-18 per km. I would recommend launching at Rs 15 per km for the first 60-90 days to build supply and demand simultaneously, then increasing to Rs 18 once the network is established.`},{s:`I`,t:`How would you structure the actual launch?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three phases: first, supply onboarding — recruit 500-1,000 drivers in Gurgaon through referral incentives and guaranteed earning schemes for the first two months to reduce driver-side risk. Second, demand activation — offer a free first ride to all app users within 3 km of Gurgaon metro stations; run corporate outreach to Cyber City and DLF Cyber Hub offices to sign up bulk employee users. Third, safety and trust — implement driver background verification, mandatory helmet enforcement, and an in-app emergency SOS feature before launch. Female commuters are a key target segment for last-mile connectivity, and safety features are non-negotiable for their adoption.`}]},
  {id:25,title:`US Chemical Company — India Market Entry Evaluation`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Chemicals`,problem:`Your client is a US-based chemical company that manufactures a patented snow-melting chemical used in snowfall-affected regions. They are evaluating whether to enter the Indian market. Assess the opportunity.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a US chemical company with a patented snow-melting chemical. They are evaluating India as a new market. The product price is $0.50 per litre. Assess the opportunity.`},{s:`C`,t:`The first question is whether sufficient demand exists in India. Snowfall in India is limited to high-altitude regions — primarily Jammu and Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, and parts of the North-East. The primary application would be road and highway de-icing. Let me size the market.`},{s:`I`,t:`The regions with significant annual snowfall — above 100 cm per year — cover approximately 20% of the mountain belt states. Assume 100 cm of snowfall per year and that 1 litre of chemical is required per 10 square metres of area to clear effectively.`},{s:`C`,t:`India's total area is approximately 3.29 million square km. Snowfall-affected regions represent roughly 1-2% of India's land, say 35,000-65,000 square km. Converting to square metres: 35,000 square km equals 35 billion square metres. At 1 litre per 10 square metres, the volume needed is approximately 3.5 billion litres per season. At $0.50 per litre, the market value is approximately $1.75 billion — a meaningful opportunity for a niche chemical product.`},{s:`I`,t:`That is an attractive number. How would you evaluate the entry decision?`},{s:`C`,t:`Beyond market size, I would examine: first, the competitive landscape — are there existing suppliers currently serving road maintenance authorities in these states? If current practice is manual clearing or plain salt, the client faces the challenge of switching established procurement patterns. Second, the distribution model — reaching state government road departments in remote mountain areas requires either direct government contracting or a local distribution partner. Third, regulatory clearance for chemical use in environmentally sensitive mountain regions. My recommendation would be a pilot entry in Himachal Pradesh or Jammu and Kashmir, targeting the state PWD through a government supply contract, with a local distributor partner to manage logistics.`}]},
  {id:26,title:`Ice Cream Brand — Stadium Stall at National Cricket Tournament`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`FMCG`,problem:`Our client is a well-known ice cream brand serving the mid-to-high income segment with outlets across India. They are evaluating setting up a stall inside a cricket stadium hosting matches of a major national T20 tournament. The stadium seats 40,000 spectators at 80% average occupancy, with 10 home matches per season. Average ice cream price: Rs 60. Evaluate the opportunity.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is an ice cream brand evaluating a stadium stall. Capacity: 40,000 seats, 80% occupancy, 10 home matches per season. Average ice cream price: Rs 60. Evaluate the opportunity.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will assess this across three dimensions: revenue and profitability, operational feasibility, and strategic value. On revenue: at 80% occupancy the stadium holds 32,000 spectators per match. What proportion are likely to buy?`},{s:`I`,t:`Assume 25% of spectators buy one ice cream per match. Affordability at Rs 60 is not a concern for this audience.`},{s:`C`,t:`At 25% conversion: 32,000 times 25% equals 8,000 units at Rs 60, giving Rs 4.8 lakh per match. Over 10 home matches, total seasonal revenue is Rs 48 lakh. At a gross margin of approximately 50% for branded ice cream at volume pricing, gross profit is approximately Rs 24 lakh per season. This needs to be set against stall lease, staffing, and equipment costs. Are stall lease terms available?`},{s:`I`,t:`Stall lease is not specified. Assume it is manageable within the gross profit. What operational challenges concern you most?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three critical challenges: first, peak demand concentration — most purchases happen within the first 30 minutes and during each innings break. Two to three kiosks with pre-stocked freezer trolleys are needed to serve 1,000-1,500 customers in a 15-minute window. Second, cold chain reliability — maintaining below minus 18 degrees Celsius throughout a four-hour outdoor match in Indian conditions requires backup generator power; a failure wastes an entire match's inventory. Third, waste management — with a 25% purchase rate, overstocking by even 10-15% creates material waste costs; accurate demand forecasting by match type is important.`},{s:`I`,t:`What is your overall recommendation?`},{s:`C`,t:`Proceed, starting with two to three kiosks at the stadium entrance and main concourse. The Rs 24 lakh seasonal gross profit is meaningful, but the brand visibility to 32,000 affluent fans per match across a nationally televised event may deliver comparable long-term value. Monitor sell-through after the first two matches and adjust inventory levels accordingly. If unit economics are positive, expand to additional venues in the following season.`}]},
  {id:27,title:`Korean Fertilizer Company — Pricing for US Apple Market`,type:`Pricing`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Agriculture`,problem:`A Korean conglomerate has developed a patented fertiliser that reduces the apple growing cycle by 20% — from 90 days to 72 days. No competing product exists. They plan to sell through US retail chains. Help price the product for US apple farmers.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`A Korean conglomerate has a patented fertiliser reducing apple growing cycles from 90 to 72 days. No competitor exists. They plan to sell through US retail chains at an application rate of 1 kg per acre per additional cycle. Help price it.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since there are no direct competitors and the product has a patent, I will use value-based pricing anchored on the economic benefit to the farmer. The benefit is one additional growing cycle per year. What is the incremental revenue a farmer earns from that additional cycle?`},{s:`I`,t:`Assume the incremental revenue is $200 per acre for the additional cycle.`},{s:`C`,t:`The farmer gains $200 per acre per additional cycle. The maximum they would pay for the fertiliser is anything below that $200 — the price at which the net benefit is still positive. To determine the actual recommended price, I would apply a value-sharing principle: the company captures a portion, and the farmer retains a meaningful net benefit to ensure adoption. At what do other premium agricultural inputs trade in terms of the percentage of value they capture?`},{s:`I`,t:`In agricultural input markets, premium inputs typically capture 60-80% of the incremental value they create.`},{s:`C`,t:`Using 80% value capture: the price would be $200 times 80% equals $160 per kg. This leaves the farmer a net benefit of $40 per acre per additional cycle — a meaningful incentive to adopt. The recommended launch price is $160 per kg. This should be validated against the client's manufacturing and logistics cost structure to ensure a sufficient margin. Does the client have a patent to protect this price point?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, the product is fully patented. No similar product exists.`},{s:`C`,t:`With patent protection, pricing power is strong for the patent duration. Recommended go-to-market: partner with established US agricultural supply chains — Agrium, The Andersons, or Nutrien — for retail distribution to reach farmers efficiently. In the first season, offer a demonstration programme providing subsidised product to 20-30 farms in Washington State, the largest US apple-producing region, to generate adoption data and farmer testimonials. This peer-to-peer evidence is the most credible marketing tool in the agricultural sector.`}]},
  {id:28,title:`South African Telecom — Revenue Shortfall in East African Market`,type:`Growth Strategy`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Telecom`,problem:`Your client is the leading telecom operator in South Africa with 35% domestic market share. Two years ago it entered an East African market targeting 10% market share but has achieved only 4%. Revenue is significantly below target. Market growth has been in line with expectations. The shortfall is competitive. Identify the cause and suggest a growth strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is the leading South African telecom operator. Entered an East African market two years ago targeting 10% market share but achieved only 4%. Revenue well below target. Market growing as expected. Shortfall is competitive.`},{s:`C`,t:`The 6-percentage-point gap in a market growing as expected means the client is losing to local operators on competitiveness. I will investigate three areas: pricing, product relevance, and cost structure. Are the client's tariffs higher than local operators?`},{s:`I`,t:`Slightly higher, yes.`},{s:`C`,t:`Higher prices in a price-sensitive East African market impair subscriber acquisition. Why are prices higher — is it a higher cost base?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The client imported its South African network equipment and IT systems, which cost more than locally sourced alternatives used by domestic operators.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a cost-structure mismatch — the client applied its home-market operating model without adjusting for local input economics. On the product side: what services does the dominant local operator offer that the client does not?`},{s:`I`,t:`The client does not offer mobile money. The local incumbent runs a dominant mobile money platform embedded in daily transactions — people use it for groceries, utility bills, school fees, and remittances. It is not an add-on feature; it is the primary reason millions of people choose their SIM.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a fundamental product-market fit gap. Mobile money in East Africa is not a financial service — it is infrastructure. Not offering it means the client cannot serve as the primary SIM for the majority of the population. Recommendations: first, launch a mobile money wallet within six months through a partnership with a local licensed bank or fintech — building from scratch would take 18-24 months. Second, restructure tariff pricing for local income patterns: introduce daily 20 MB data bundles and weekly 200 MB bundles at lower price points than current monthly plans. Third, invest in network coverage in secondary towns where the local incumbent has underinvested — lower competitive intensity there makes subscriber acquisition more cost-efficient.`}]},
  {id:29,title:`Online Travel Aggregator — Become India's Market Leader`,type:`Growth Strategy`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Travel & Tourism`,problem:`Your client is an online travel aggregator currently ranked second or third in India. The company charges a 1% commission to both traveller and travel agency per booking. The client wants to become the number one player within two years without increasing commission rates.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is an online travel aggregator ranked second or third in India, charging 1% commission to both the traveller and travel agency. The goal is to become India's number one player within two years, without raising commission rates.`},{s:`C`,t:`With a two-year window and no commission increase, growth must come from volume and customer stickiness. I will separate near-term actions from medium-term strategic investments. For the first six months: where does the highest-impact, lowest-investment growth come from?`},{s:`I`,t:`The client currently acquires users through online marketing and partnerships with travel agencies. The approach is similar to the market leader.`},{s:`C`,t:`If the approach mirrors the market leader, differentiation must come from service quality and value-adds rather than just marketing spend. Three near-term levers: first, improve conversion rates on existing traffic through better UX — faster search results, cleaner price comparison, and a simplified checkout reduce drop-off. Second, introduce a no-fee cancellation policy on select inventory — this is a powerful acquisition message in the Indian market where travellers are risk-averse about non-refundable bookings. Third, build out the Tier-2 and Tier-3 city presence with a vernacular-language interface in Hindi, Tamil, and Bengali — a large addressable audience currently underserved by the market leader.`},{s:`I`,t:`What are the medium-term strategic investments?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three medium-term investments: first, a loyalty programme that accumulates points across all travel categories — flights, hotels, buses, and trains — creating meaningful switching costs. High-frequency travellers who are rewarded for consolidating all bookings on one platform are the most defensible customer segment. Second, a subscription product for frequent travellers — a Rs 999 per year membership offering priority access to deals, free cancellations on one booking per month, and lounge access tie-ups — generates predictable revenue while building a loyal core user base. Third, proprietary tools for corporate travel management — a platform that handles policy compliance, expense reporting, and bulk booking for mid-sized companies — opens a high-value B2B segment that is currently underserved by the major players.`}]},
  {id:30,title:`IT Services Firm — Declining Campus Job Applications`,type:`Unconventional`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`IT & ITES`,problem:`Your client is a top-tier IT services company providing offshore ERP support. Over the past two years, the number of campus job applications from engineering students has declined significantly, despite stable job openings. The decline is specific to this company. Identify the cause and suggest corrective actions.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a top-tier IT services company. Campus job applications from engineering students have fallen significantly over two years. Job openings are stable. The decline is client-specific. Identify the cause and suggest fixes.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since the decline is client-specific, the company is less preferred than alternative employers at the same campuses. I will trace the student decision journey from awareness to application. Are the same number of students in the final year pools at target colleges aware of this company?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The company visits the same campuses. Awareness is not the issue. Fewer students among those aware are choosing to apply.`},{s:`C`,t:`So students are aware but self-selecting out. That points to either perceived employer attractiveness issues — compensation, career growth, work culture, or brand appeal — or a friction in the application process itself. Has more competition arrived on campus from employers in other sectors or product companies?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. More companies now visit these campuses — including start-ups, product companies, and non-IT sectors — giving students a wider choice. And the client has not increased its fresher salary in three years.`},{s:`C`,t:`A stale compensation benchmark combined with more attractive alternatives is the most direct driver. Engineering students comparing this company's offer to a product company or a tech start-up offering higher packages and perceived prestige would deprioritise the ERP support role. Has the company's job profile also evolved, or is it still primarily entry-level ERP configuration and support work?`},{s:`I`,t:`The profile has not changed significantly. And I should mention the company recently moved to an online recruitment process which has been experiencing technical issues.`},{s:`C`,t:`A broken application process is often underestimated as a deterrent — an interested student who hits technical errors on an application portal will simply apply to the next company on their list. This is the most immediately fixable issue and should be resolved before the next placement season. Three recommendations in priority order: first, fix the online application portal immediately — conduct user testing with students to identify and resolve all friction points. Second, revise fresher compensation to align with current market benchmarks — even a 15-20% increase in CTC would significantly improve the offer competitiveness. Third, reframe the career narrative: instead of positioning the role as ERP support, communicate the career path to SAP Solution Architect or Enterprise Systems Consultant within three to four years. Students value visible progression. A campus ambassador programme using engaging alumni to share their career journeys peer-to-peer would make this message far more credible than corporate presentations.`}]},
  {id:31,title:`Ministry of Tourism — Double Foreign Tourist Arrivals in Five Years`,type:`Unconventional`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Government / Public Sector`,problem:`India's Ministry of Tourism wants to double foreign tourist arrivals within the next five years. Revenue from tourism has recovered post-COVID but is growing more slowly than comparable destinations. Help develop a comprehensive strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`India's Ministry of Tourism wants to double foreign tourist arrivals in five years. Other comparable destinations have recovered to near pre-COVID levels but India's growth has been slower than expected. Develop a strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`Before structuring the strategy, I want to identify the specific barriers that are making India less preferred relative to comparable destinations. Based on traveller research, the commonly cited barriers for India are: a complex or slow visa process, inconsistent airport experience, safety concerns particularly for solo female travellers, poor infrastructure at tourist sites outside the Golden Triangle, and connectivity to Tier-2 heritage destinations. Is the Ministry aware of which barriers are most significant?`},{s:`I`,t:`All are relevant. Build your strategy around addressing them systematically.`},{s:`C`,t:`My strategy framework covers three pillars: removing barriers to entry, improving the in-country experience, and amplifying international marketing. Starting with barriers to entry: the visa process is the first filter. E-Visa exists but has inconsistent approval timelines and technical issues. I would recommend same-day e-Visa approval for citizens of the top 30 source markets — US, UK, EU, Japan, South Korea, Australia, UAE. Visa-on-arrival expansion to additional airports beyond the current six or seven would also reduce friction for spontaneous visitors.`},{s:`I`,t:`What about the in-country experience?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three key improvements: first, airport first impressions — the arrival experience at major international airports like Delhi and Mumbai sets the tone for the entire trip. Standardised pre-booked taxi services with app-based booking, multilingual signage, and a tourist information desk at every international airport would immediately improve the first impression. Second, transportation: introduce dedicated tourist corridor trains connecting the Golden Triangle — Delhi, Agra, Jaipur — with clean, punctual, and air-conditioned services. The Vande Bharat Express network could be adapted for this. Third, safety: create a dedicated Tourist Police force in the top 15 destination cities with training in multiple languages and rapid response to tourist complaints.`},{s:`I`,t:`And on marketing?`},{s:`C`,t:`India's Incredible India brand is globally recognised but not optimally targeted. I recommend a source-market-specific approach: spiritual and wellness tourism positioning for US, Japan, and Korean markets — India is the world's foremost destination for yoga, Ayurveda, and Buddhist heritage. Heritage and culture for European markets. Adventure tourism — Himalayas, wildlife safaris, desert landscapes — for younger Australian and New Zealand visitors. Each positioning should be delivered through local-language influencers native to the source market rather than generic government advertising. India's current tourism promotion budget of approximately $200 million annually is significantly lower than Thailand's $500 million or the UAE's $1 billion — increasing this investment alongside the structural improvements above is what will create compounding growth.`}]},
  {id:32,title:`Analytics Firm Founder — Acquisition Offer from an FMCG Conglomerate`,type:`M&A`,difficulty:`Hard`,sector:`Technology`,problem:`Your client is the founder of an analytics firm providing consumer insights and demand forecasting to FMCG companies. The firm has revenues of $15 million growing at 35% per year. A large FMCG conglomerate has offered a buyout at $75 million — a 5x revenue multiple. Industry average P/S multiple is 4.5x. No other offers have been received. Help the founder evaluate whether to accept.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Analytics firm founder: $15M revenues, 35% annual growth. FMCG conglomerate has offered $75M buyout — 5x revenue. Industry average is 4.5x. No other offers received. Help evaluate.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will evaluate across two dimensions: financial attractiveness and strategic considerations. Financially: the 5x multiple exceeds the 4.5x industry average — attractive on the surface. However, at 35% annual growth the trajectory matters more than the current snapshot. At this rate, revenues reach $30M in two years. At a 4.5x multiple, fair value would then be $135M — the $75M offer today represents a significant discount to that trajectory-implied value.`},{s:`I`,t:`Good point. Is there additional context that should factor into the financial assessment?`},{s:`C`,t:`Key question: is there a near-term contract win that would accelerate the revenue trajectory materially? Does the firm have any large pending contracts with the acquirer or similar clients?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes — there is a 70% probability of winning a major data analytics contract worth $12 million from a direct competitor of the acquirer. If won, revenues would increase to approximately $27 million within 12 months.`},{s:`C`,t:`At $27M revenues, fair value at 4.5x would be $121M. The $75M offer looks significantly underpriced in that scenario. The founder should either delay accepting until the contract outcome is known — two to three months — or negotiate an earn-out structure: a base price of $75M plus $35-40M payable if revenues cross $25M within 18 months of closing.`},{s:`I`,t:`Noted. What strategic and personal factors matter?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three strategic questions: first, post-acquisition culture risk — this FMCG conglomerate is a traditional business, not a technology company. Analytics firms depend on talent autonomy and fast iteration; embedding this team in a large corporate structure risks key employee attrition, which is the firm's core value. Negotiate a three to five year operational autonomy clause. Second, acquirer fit — are there better-suited buyers? A marketing technology platform, a management consultancy, or a PE sponsor focused on B2B SaaS would likely offer a higher multiple and better operational synergy. Third, the founder's personal goals: if financial independence is the primary objective, even a $75M partial exit is transformative. If the goal is to build a scaled independent business, a growth equity round at a higher valuation following the contract win is the better path.`}]},
  {id:33,title:`Beer Manufacturer — Manufacturing Cost Above International Benchmarks`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Easy`,sector:`FMCG`,problem:`Your client is a beer manufacturing company operating in India with multiple products and three plants, each running at full capacity. Manufacturing cost per unit is significantly above international benchmarks for the same production scale. Identify the root cause.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is an Indian beer manufacturer with three plants at 100% capacity. Manufacturing cost per unit is significantly above international benchmarks. Identify why.`},{s:`C`,t:`Is the cost gap concentrated in a specific cost head — processing, energy, raw materials, logistics — or spread across multiple areas?`},{s:`I`,t:`The gap is in manufacturing and processing costs specifically. Distribution, raw materials, and marketing are in line with benchmarks.`},{s:`C`,t:`Within processing costs, the main levers are batch size, capacity utilisation, machine efficiency, energy consumption, and labour productivity. The client is at 100% utilisation — what is the output per batch compared to international plants at similar overall scale?`},{s:`I`,t:`Each of the three plants produces approximately 20,000 cases per batch. International competitors operating at comparable aggregate capacity produce 40,000 to 70,000 cases per batch.`},{s:`C`,t:`The gap is in batch size, not utilisation rate. Running at 100% of a small batch means fixed costs — depreciation, utilities, plant overheads — are spread over fewer cases, raising cost per unit significantly. Is the small batch size because the machines are undersized, or because the plant floor plan cannot accommodate larger machines?`},{s:`I`,t:`The plant floor plans cannot accommodate the newer high-throughput machines, which have a larger physical footprint than the current layout allows.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a capital infrastructure constraint, not an operational one. Two recommendations: short term — increase daily operating shifts from two to three. This does not change batch size but maximises annual throughput within the existing footprint, spreading fixed costs over approximately 50% more annual output and reducing cost per case meaningfully. Medium to long term — build new plants designed to accommodate high-throughput machinery producing 50,000+ cases per batch, or structurally renovate existing plants to expand floor space. The unit economics improve dramatically once batch size reaches 40,000+ cases; this capital investment should be modelled against the NPV of the cost savings over a ten-year horizon.`}]},
  {id:34,title:`Retail Bank — Declining Profits at a Metropolitan Branch`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`BFSI`,problem:`Our client is a major retail bank. One of its metropolitan branches has seen a 20% decline in profits over the past year. The issue is specific to this branch. Competitors in the same area are unaffected. Help identify the root cause and suggest solutions.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a major retail bank. One metro branch has seen a 20% profit decline over the past year. This is branch-specific. Competitors are unaffected. Find the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since the problem is branch-specific, it rules out market-level causes. Is the decline driven by falling revenues or by rising costs?`},{s:`I`,t:`Costs have increased significantly at this branch. Revenue has been stable.`},{s:`C`,t:`For a bank branch, the main variable cost driver is the time spent by staff servicing customer transactions. Have transaction volumes increased, or has the time per transaction grown?`},{s:`I`,t:`Transaction volumes have remained stable. The time spent per customer interaction has increased significantly.`},{s:`C`,t:`Higher time per interaction with stable volumes means each customer visit consumes more employee hours than before. This would raise the effective cost of service without generating additional revenue. Why would handling time increase — is it that queries have become more complex, or that staff cannot resolve issues in a single visit?`},{s:`I`,t:`Staff are unable to resolve many customer requests in a single visit. Customers return multiple times for the same service request, which multiplies the total staff time consumed per case.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a training and process design issue. Customers requiring multiple visits for a single service request means either staff lack the knowledge to complete the request end-to-end, or there are process or system bottlenecks that prevent single-visit resolution. Three recommendations: first, identify the top five service request types driving repeat visits and create simple step-by-step resolution playbooks that any staff member can execute. Second, implement a single-window or universal banking model — one staff member handles the customer from entry to exit rather than bouncing them between specialist desks. Third, deploy self-service kiosks for routine transactions — cash deposit, passbook update, fund transfer — freeing staff to focus on complex requests. Tracking first-visit resolution rate as a KPI and setting a target above 85% would drive measurable improvement.`}]},
  {id:35,title:`Auto Insurance Company — Declining Profitability`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Insurance`,problem:`Your client is a top-six auto insurance company in India. It has been experiencing declining profitability for two years. Revenue has grown in line with the industry. Competitors have not reported similar challenges. Help identify the problem and suggest solutions.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a top-6 auto insurer in India. Profitability is declining over two years. Revenue grows in line with industry. Competitors are unaffected. Find the problem.`},{s:`C`,t:`Since revenue is growing in line with industry, the issue is cost-side. For an insurance company, the primary cost driver is claims settlement. Has the claims cost grown faster than premiums?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes — claims settlement costs have been growing significantly faster than premium income.`},{s:`C`,t:`Claims cost can be decomposed into: number of claims times average payout per claim. Has the average payout per claim changed?`},{s:`I`,t:`Average payout is unchanged. The frequency of claims — the probability of a policyholder making a claim — has increased.`},{s:`C`,t:`Higher claims frequency without a change in payout indicates a shift in the risk profile of the customer portfolio. I would segment the portfolio by age group, income bracket, vehicle type, and geography to identify which segment is driving the excess claims. In auto insurance, young drivers under 25 have statistically two to three times higher accident rates than 35-55 year old drivers. Has the proportion of young policyholders in the portfolio grown?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The under-25 segment has grown as a proportion of the portfolio and this group has been involved in significantly more accidents due to aggressive driving behaviour.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a portfolio concentration risk in the highest-frequency cohort. Three recommendations: first, immediately revise premiums for the under-25 segment upward to reflect the actuarial risk differential — this restores underwriting margin on new policies in this segment. Second, introduce telematics-based pricing — where a young driver installs an in-app driving monitor and earns a premium discount for demonstrated safe driving — which simultaneously incentivises safer behaviour and differentiates the client from competitors on innovation. Third, actively grow the portfolio in lower-risk segments: middle-aged drivers with clean claims histories, corporate fleet accounts with professional driver policies, and geographies with historically lower accident rates. This diversification reduces concentration risk and improves the overall loss ratio over the medium term.`}]},
  {id:36,title:`South African Education Provider — Enrolment Decline`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Education`,problem:`Your client is a South African private education provider offering post-secondary undergraduate and postgraduate programmes in business and management. It is the third-largest player among six competitors. Revenues have been declining driven by falling enrolments. Identify the cause and define a revival plan.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a South African education provider, third in market, offering business and management programmes across urban provinces. Revenues declining. Identify why and define a revival plan.`},{s:`C`,t:`Education revenues come primarily from enrolment fees, research grants, and donations. Which stream is declining?`},{s:`I`,t:`The decline is in enrolments. Research and donations are stable.`},{s:`C`,t:`Enrolment decline can stem from fewer applications, lower offer acceptance, or higher mid-programme dropout. Which is it?`},{s:`I`,t:`Fewer students are enrolling in undergraduate programmes. The problem is concentrated in the coastal provinces where manufacturing and port logistics industries are the major employers.`},{s:`C`,t:`A province-specific decline in a region dominated by manufacturing and logistics suggests a curriculum-employment mismatch. Are graduates from this provider finding it harder to compete in a job market that values both management and operational or technical skills?`},{s:`I`,t:`Correct. Competitors in those provinces offer a higher-level technical certification integrated into their business degrees — covering supply chain operations, logistics technology, or industrial management — which our client does not offer.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is a curriculum relevance gap. Students and families are making a rational choice to enrol with competitors who offer a qualification better aligned with local employment opportunities, and fees are broadly comparable across players. Three recommendations: first, introduce a technical specialisation track as an elective module within the undergraduate programme — supply chain management, port logistics, or operations analytics — developed in consultation with regional employers. This can be done within one academic cycle without a full redesign. Second, build formal employer partnerships in those coastal provinces: placement agreements with manufacturers and logistics companies create visible employment outcomes that directly drive enrolment decisions. Third, update marketing materials to lead with placement data — employer names, average starting salaries, sector placement rates — rather than academic rankings. At this level, measurable employment outcomes are the primary enrolment driver.`}]},
  {id:37,title:`Tractor Manufacturer — Declining Sales in Southern India`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Automobiles`,problem:`Our client is a major tractor manufacturer with pan-India presence distributing through indirect retail channels. The company is experiencing a specific decline in revenue from the Southern India market. Identify the root cause and suggest solutions.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Our client is a tractor manufacturer with pan-India distribution through dealers. Revenue is declining specifically in Southern India. The company sells a single tractor model for the rural segment. Identify the cause.`},{s:`C`,t:`Is the decline in units sold, or in realisation per unit? And is it across all states in the South, or concentrated in specific states?`},{s:`I`,t:`Units sold have fallen across Southern India broadly. Realisation per unit is unchanged.`},{s:`C`,t:`For a tractor, the purchase decision is typically enabled by financing — most farmers purchase on a loan from a bank, NBFC, or cooperative credit society. Has there been any change in the financing environment for agricultural equipment in the South?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. Last year there was a wave of agricultural loan defaults in Southern India, causing local banks and NBFCs to significantly tighten lending standards and raise interest rates for agricultural equipment purchases.`},{s:`C`,t:`That is the root cause — a credit contraction in the agricultural lending market has reduced the number of farmers who can access financing to buy a tractor. The client's product and distribution are not the issue; it is an exogenous credit-cycle-driven volume decline. What can the client do independently of the banking sector?`},{s:`I`,t:`Please suggest options the client can control.`},{s:`C`,t:`Three options: first, develop a company-backed EMI scheme in partnership with an NBFC — where the manufacturer takes partial credit risk alongside the lender to improve approval rates for farmer borrowers. This is similar to the auto manufacturer captive financing model used by Mahindra Finance. Second, introduce a lease-to-own product for Southern India specifically: farmers use the tractor and pay a monthly lease from their harvest income rather than taking an upfront loan. This removes the dependency on traditional bank lending entirely. Third, partner with Farmer Producer Organisations and cooperative societies in the South to offer group financing arrangements — where a group of farmers collectively backs individual loans, reducing default risk and improving lender willingness to disburse. Each of these puts the client in greater control of its own sales volume rather than being purely dependent on external credit availability.`}]},
  {id:38,title:`Diagnostic Chain Mumbai — Declining Profitability at South Mumbai Centre`,type:`Profitability`,difficulty:`Easy`,sector:`Healthcare`,problem:`Your client is a diagnostic chain with four centres across Mumbai offering pathological and radiological services. Profitability has been declining for five months. Identify the issue and suggest recommendations.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a Mumbai diagnostic chain with four centres offering pathological and radiological services. Profitability declining for five months. Costs unchanged. Identify the issue.`},{s:`C`,t:`Is the decline spread across all four centres, or concentrated in one?`},{s:`I`,t:`The issue is specific to the South Mumbai centre, which contributes 45% of total revenue. Patient footfall there has fallen significantly.`},{s:`C`,t:`For a diagnostic centre, patients arrive through two channels: direct walk-ins and referrals from doctors and local clinics. Which channel has fallen?`},{s:`I`,t:`Referrals from three nearby specialty clinics have dropped sharply. These clinics collectively provided over 80% of the South Mumbai centre's patient volume.`},{s:`C`,t:`A simultaneous drop from three clinics points to a systemic change in how those clinics handle patients, rather than a breakdown with any individual doctor. Has there been a technology or process change at those clinics?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. All three specialty clinics have recently onboarded a telemedicine platform. Patients increasingly prefer remote consultations, which reduces the need for in-person diagnostic tests through traditional referral channels.`},{s:`C`,t:`This is a digital disruption of the referral channel — a structural shift, not a temporary dip. Recommendations: first and most immediately, apply to be listed as a partner diagnostic provider on this telemedicine platform. If the platform supports lab test ordering, being listed means patients directed to testing are routed to the client's collection centres. Second, build a strong at-home sample collection service and promote it directly to those three clinics' patient bases — this meets the convenience expectation driving telemedicine adoption without requiring patients to visit a centre. Third, offer those clinics a priority two to four-hour reporting SLA for urgent tests — physical labs can turn around complex tests faster than digital-first platforms, and making this SLA explicit gives the clinics a reason to continue routing urgent cases to the client.`}]},
  {id:39,title:`UK Online Dating App — India Market Entry`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Technology`,problem:`Your client is a UK-based online dating company operating on a freemium model. Users can access basic features for free and upgrade to premium through a monthly subscription. The company wants to enter India and needs help evaluating the opportunity and defining an entry strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a UK-based online dating app on a freemium model. It wants to enter India. Evaluate the opportunity and define an entry strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`I want to understand the client first. Is this a general dating app similar to Tinder or Bumble, or does it serve a specific niche? And has it entered any similar emerging markets recently?`},{s:`I`,t:`It is a general swipe-based dating app with a freemium model — free basic use, premium subscription available. It is not involved in any other business. Last year it entered a similarly competitive emerging market and captured 7% market share in the first year.`},{s:`C`,t:`Useful benchmark. My framework covers: market sizing, competitive landscape, pricing and positioning, and go-to-market approach. Starting with market size: India has roughly 950 million people. The addressable audience for a dating app is urban, digitally active adults aged 18-40. Filtering for urban population at 35%, smartphone users at 65% of that, and applying a social openness factor of roughly 75% to adjust for India's more conservative social norms around dating, I arrive at approximately 420 million people. Does that sizing approach sound reasonable?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. Use 420 million as the base. How much of this is a paying market?`},{s:`C`,t:`Dating app global conversion from free to paid averages 5-10%. In India, given lower income levels, a conservative 3-5% conversion is appropriate. That gives approximately 12-21 million potential paid subscribers. At a price of Rs 400-450 per quarter — benchmarking against Indian market leaders who charge around Rs 400-450 for three months — the annual revenue potential is approximately Rs 1,800 to Rs 4,700 crore. Using the 7% market share benchmark from the prior emerging market entry, a realistic year-one target is 0.5-1 million paid subscribers, generating Rs 200-450 crore in annual subscription revenue.`},{s:`I`,t:`Good. What about pricing and positioning?`},{s:`C`,t:`I recommend an introductory price of Rs 349 for three months at launch — slightly below the market leader — to drive initial paid conversions. The free tier must be genuinely functional to build the user base quickly, because network effects are critical in dating apps: thin user pools create poor match experiences and drive churn. Target cities for launch: Mumbai, Delhi, Bengaluru, and Hyderabad, where the target demographic is densest. On go-to-market: partner with telecom providers for in-app billing to eliminate credit card dependency, which is a major barrier in India. Use Instagram and YouTube influencers in the 22-30 age segment for awareness — earned media from relatable creators is far more effective in this category than traditional advertising.`},{s:`I`,t:`What are the key risks?`},{s:`C`,t:`Two key risks: first, cultural sensitivity — India's diverse regional attitudes toward dating mean content moderation, community guidelines, and trust-building around safety are non-negotiable. The platform must invest significantly in safety features — verified profiles, block and report functionality, and an emergency contact feature — before launch. Second, competition from Indian apps — Truly Madly and Woo have cultural customisation and local insights that a new entrant must match. Differentiating on safety features and product quality, rather than price alone, is the sustainable positioning.`}]},
  {id:40,title:`Harvard Business School — India Satellite Campus Feasibility`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Easy`,sector:`Education`,problem:`Harvard Business School wants to set up a new satellite campus in India within five years. They want your assessment of whether they should proceed and how.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Harvard Business School wants to set up a satellite campus in India within five years. Should they proceed and how?`},{s:`C`,t:`My evaluation framework covers four dimensions: demand and market attractiveness, regulatory environment, operational feasibility, and competitive dynamics. Starting with demand: what is HBS's primary objective — increasing the proportion of Indian students globally, serving the Indian corporate sector through executive education, or both?`},{s:`I`,t:`The primary mission is consistent with HBS globally — educating future leaders. The India campus would increase the proportion of Indian students in the HBS ecosystem, which is underrepresented relative to India's growing economic weight.`},{s:`C`,t:`On demand: India produces approximately two lakh CAT applicants annually seeking top business school admissions. If 1% meet HBS's stringent international standards — GMAT above 730, strong work experience, academic excellence — that is roughly 2,000 potential applicants per year. A satellite batch of 100-150 students would be well-supported by this pool. On regulation: the National Education Policy 2020 now permits foreign universities to set up campuses in India. What are the constraints on degree-granting?`},{s:`I`,t:`The campus cannot grant a degree equivalent to the full two-year HBS residential programme. It would operate on a certificate or one-year diploma model, similar to the Indian School of Business.`},{s:`C`,t:`The ISB model is actually very instructive. ISB does not grant a formal degree but has exceptional placement outcomes and brand recognition globally. HBS has a stronger brand than ISB, which means a similar one-year programme under the HBS name would be highly sought after. On competitive dynamics: IIM-A, IIM-B, IIM-C, and ISB are the primary competitors, all offering well-regarded programmes. HBS's case method pedagogy, global alumni network, and brand would provide genuine differentiation. Should HBS proceed?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. What is your recommended approach?`},{s:`C`,t:`I recommend a phased approach to manage risk and build market presence. Phase one: launch an executive education centre in Mumbai or Bengaluru offering two to five-day leadership programmes for senior executives. No regulatory barriers apply, the programmes are immediately profitable, and this establishes the HBS brand in India with corporate clients who would later send their employees to a longer programme. Phase two: after two to three years of executive education, launch a full one-year management programme for early-career leaders using Phase one's corporate relationships for placements and sponsorships. Phase three: evaluate a full physical campus once the programme is established. This staged approach minimises the upfront infrastructure investment and allows HBS to test the market before committing.`}]},
  {id:41,title:`Electric Bus Manufacturer — India Market Entry via Ahmedabad`,type:`Market Entry`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Transport`,problem:`Your client is an international manufacturer of electric buses with strong European market presence. Impressed by India's EV incentive framework, they want to enter India starting with Ahmedabad. Evaluate the opportunity and recommend an entry approach.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client manufactures electric buses for European public transport. They want to enter India starting with Ahmedabad, leveraging the Government of India's EV incentives including FAME II subsidies and a five-year tax holiday. No electric bus operators exist at scale in India. Evaluate the opportunity.`},{s:`C`,t:`I want to confirm: the client's electric buses are technology-proven in Europe. The question is whether the product fits the Indian context and how to execute market entry effectively. Is that correct?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes. The technology is mature and certified in Europe. The challenge is adapting for India and finding the right entry model.`},{s:`C`,t:`On product-market fit: European electric buses are designed for well-maintained roads and temperatures below 35 degrees Celsius. Indian urban roads present different challenges — variable road quality requiring reinforced suspension, ambient temperatures of 40-45 degrees Celsius that reduce battery efficiency, and dust and humidity exposure. Has the client assessed these adaptation requirements?`},{s:`I`,t:`Not yet. Customisation for Indian conditions would be required.`},{s:`C`,t:`That adaptation is the critical pre-entry action. I would recommend partnering with an Indian engineering firm or the Indian subsidiary of a European automotive supplier to co-develop India-specific modifications: battery management systems optimised for high ambient temperatures, suspension and chassis reinforcement for Indian road conditions, and driver control interfaces in local languages. On the financial attractiveness: the FAME II scheme subsidises up to Rs 50 lakh per electric bus for public transport operators. For state transport undertakings like Ahmedabad's AMTS, which evaluate on lifecycle cost, the subsidy brings the total cost of ownership of an electric bus close to parity with a diesel bus over a 10-year ownership period, making the case compelling.`},{s:`I`,t:`What entry model would you recommend?`},{s:`C`,t:`I strongly recommend a joint venture or formal partnership with an established Indian commercial vehicle manufacturer — Tata Motors or Ashok Leyland are the natural candidates. Both have existing relationships with state transport corporations, established dealer and service networks, and the manufacturing footprint to achieve the local content requirements necessary for FAME II subsidy eligibility. The client brings the core electric drivetrain and battery technology; the Indian partner brings the market access, regulatory relationships, and after-sales infrastructure. Start with a 50-100 bus pilot with AMTS in Ahmedabad, collect performance data over one monsoon and one summer season, and use this reference deployment to bid for Smart Cities Mission bus electrification tenders in Pune, Surat, and Vadodara.`}]},
  {id:42,title:`Heli-Air Taxi Service — Pricing and Business Viability in Delhi`,type:`Pricing`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Aviation`,problem:`Your client operates helicopter taxi services in London, Dubai, and São Paulo. They are considering launching in Delhi between two city points. Operating plan: one helicopter, 25 working days per month, 4 round trips per day. Fixed costs: helicopter rental Rs 18 lakh per month, airport charges Rs 2.5 lakh per month, crew salaries Rs 4.5 lakh per month, insurance and overheads Rs 1 lakh per month. Price the service and assess viability.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client wants to launch helicopter taxi services in Delhi. Helicopter rental: Rs 18L/month. Airport charges: Rs 2.5L/month. Crew salaries: Rs 4.5L/month. Overheads: Rs 1L/month. 25 operating days, 4 round trips per day. Price the service and assess viability.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will triangulate using three approaches: cost-based to set the floor, competitor-based as a market check, and value-based to test the ceiling. Starting with cost-based: total fixed costs per month are Rs 18 + 2.5 + 4.5 + 1 = Rs 26 lakh. At 4 round trips per day and 25 days, we have 100 trips per month. Variable fuel cost for a light helicopter covering 35-40 km per trip at current ATF prices is approximately Rs 7,000-8,000. At Rs 7,500 per trip, variable monthly cost is Rs 7.5 lakh. Total monthly cost: Rs 33.5 lakh.`},{s:`I`,t:`How many passengers per trip, and what does that imply for per-seat pricing?`},{s:`C`,t:`A standard light helicopter carries 4 passengers. Breakeven per trip is Rs 33.5 lakh divided by 100 trips = Rs 33,500. Per seat that is Rs 8,375. Adding a 25% margin gives Rs 10,470 per seat — I would recommend Rs 11,000 as a clean price point.`},{s:`I`,t:`How would you validate this against customer willingness to pay?`},{s:`C`,t:`Value-based check: a senior executive travelling between central Delhi and Gurgaon faces 45-90 minutes of peak-hour road congestion. A helicopter reduces this to under 15 minutes — a saving of 30-75 minutes. For an executive whose time is valued at Rs 6,000-12,000 per hour, that saving is worth Rs 3,000-15,000 per trip. At Rs 11,000 per seat, the service is well within the value range for C-suite executives, senior bankers, and high-net-worth individuals. Competitor check: equivalent services in Mumbai's premium segment charge Rs 9,000-16,000 per seat, confirming Rs 11,000 is market-consistent.`},{s:`I`,t:`Is the business viable at these economics?`},{s:`C`,t:`At Rs 11,000 per seat with 4 seats and 100 trips monthly, full-capacity revenue is Rs 44 lakh against Rs 33.5 lakh costs — a Rs 10.5 lakh monthly operating profit and a 24% margin. However, 100% seat occupancy is aggressive in year one. At 70% occupancy — 280 seats per month — revenue is Rs 30.8 lakh, which falls below the Rs 33.5 lakh cost base. The service only becomes financially viable above approximately 77% seat occupancy. Recommendation: secure two to three corporate anchor clients through annual minimum-usage agreements — say 30 confirmed trips per month each — before launch. This de-risks the occupancy assumption. Without committed corporate demand, the business should not launch.`}]},
  {id:43,title:`Elevator Manufacturer — Responding to a New Market Entrant`,type:`Growth Strategy`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Manufacturing`,problem:`Your client is a well-known elevator manufacturer that has dominated the European and US markets for over 20 years. A new competitor has entered the market with innovative products and is steadily eroding market share. Help develop a competitive growth strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a 20-year dominant elevator manufacturer in Europe and the US. A new competitor has entered with IoT-enabled, energy-efficient elevators and faster installation, and is taking market share. The competitor is focusing on Asian markets. The client's R&D spend is 2% of revenue versus the competitor's 8%. Develop a competitive strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`The problem has two components: domestic market share erosion due to a product innovation gap, and a missed opportunity in high-growth Asian markets. Let me address both. On the product gap: the 2% versus 8% R&D spend differential explains the innovation lag. The client needs to accelerate R&D investment toward 5-6% of revenue with focused priorities on the two capabilities where the gap is most damaging — IoT-based predictive maintenance and energy-efficient drive systems.`},{s:`I`,t:`Why those two specifically?`},{s:`C`,t:`IoT-based predictive maintenance is the feature that commercial building operators value most — it reduces unexpected downtime which is extremely disruptive in high-rise office and residential buildings. Energy-efficient drives reduce operating costs for building owners in a cost-sensitive environment. Both are tangible, quantifiable benefits that justify switching from the incumbent. The client should bring these capabilities to market within 18-24 months, supplemented by a software-based remote monitoring offering that creates a recurring revenue stream through annual maintenance contracts.`},{s:`I`,t:`What about the Asian market opportunity?`},{s:`C`,t:`Southeast Asia — Vietnam, Indonesia, Philippines — and South Asia — India — have construction booms underway with millions of square metres of commercial and residential high-rise being built annually. The client's 20-year brand equity and global track record with major construction companies in Europe and the US can be leveraged to secure introductions to international developers building in Asia. The fastest route to market in Asia is acquiring a mid-sized local elevator company with an existing sales and service network — this avoids the multi-year greenfield ramp-up. The acquired company gains the client's technology and brand; the client gains immediate market access and a trained service network.`},{s:`I`,t:`How should the client protect its existing domestic customer base in the meantime?`},{s:`C`,t:`Three actions: first, proactively reach out to the top 200 existing long-term clients with enhanced multi-year maintenance contract renewals before they have a conversation with the competitor. The relationship and track record give the client an advantage at renewal time. Second, launch a retrofit and modernisation programme — upgrading existing elevators in the installed base with IoT sensors and new drive systems. This generates near-term revenue from the installed base and demonstrates innovation credibility to current customers. Third, for new builds where the competitor is competitive on the innovation spec, consider targeted price adjustments on the initial installation contract while protecting long-term maintenance contract margins — the lifecycle revenue from maintenance is where profitability lies.`}]},
  {id:44,title:`2 and 3-Wheeler Manufacturer — Achieving 15% CAGR Growth`,type:`Growth Strategy`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Automobiles`,problem:`Your client is a pan-India manufacturer of two-wheelers and three-wheelers. Product mix: electric three-wheelers 60% of revenue, scooters 30%, bikes 10%. The company is growing at 4-5% while the industry grows at 9-10%. Management wants 15% CAGR. Develop a strategy.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client manufactures electric three-wheelers (60% of revenue), scooters (30%), and bikes (10%). Growth is 4-5% vs industry at 9-10%. Management wants 15% CAGR. The client holds dominant share in electric three-wheelers. Develop a strategy.`},{s:`C`,t:`There are two distinct problems: the electric three-wheeler market is growing slowly despite the client's dominant position, and the scooter segment is growing but the client is underperforming. Starting with electric three-wheelers: with dominant share in a stagnant market, growth cannot come from gaining share — the market itself needs to expand. What is constraining electric three-wheeler market growth?`},{s:`I`,t:`Electric three-wheelers depend on charging infrastructure. Reliable stations are only available in five to six major metro cities, limiting the addressable market geographically.`},{s:`C`,t:`The market is supply-constrained by infrastructure, not demand-constrained. Electric three-wheelers are economically very attractive — operating costs are 60-70% lower than CNG three-wheelers — but operators in Tier-2 and Tier-3 cities cannot adopt them without charging access. The client, with dominant market share, benefits disproportionately from every city that becomes viable for electric three-wheelers. Strategy: work actively with state electricity boards and the Ministry of Power to co-invest in charging infrastructure across 25-35 additional cities. Use industry advocacy channels to accelerate government funding for electric three-wheeler charging in smaller cities.`},{s:`I`,t:`And on scooters?`},{s:`C`,t:`The scooter market is at an inflection point — EV scooters now exceed 12% of all scooter sales and are growing at 40%+ annually, driven by Ola Electric and Ather. If the client sells only ICE scooters, it is competing in a shrinking segment of a growing market. The essential action is entering the EV scooter segment within 18-24 months. The client already has battery and motor expertise from the electric three-wheeler business — this is a genuine capability transfer, not a cold start. An EV scooter at Rs 85,000-1,10,000 would compete in the mass-market sweet spot.`},{s:`I`,t:`What if the client prefers acquisition over in-house development?`},{s:`C`,t:`Acquisition is faster. Several EV scooter start-ups have viable products but lack manufacturing scale and capital — brands like Greaves Electric or Okinawa Autotech could be acquired at reasonable valuations given the recent market correction in EV start-up valuations. For the ICE scooter range in the interim: add digital instrument clusters, Bluetooth connectivity, and USB charging — now table-stakes expectations for buyers under 30 — and intensify digital marketing to counter Honda Activa and TVS Jupiter's stronger brand presence. The combined strategy — electric three-wheeler geographic expansion, EV scooter entry, ICE scooter refresh — creates the path to 15% CAGR.`}]},
  {id:45,title:`EPC Company — Five-Year Expansion Strategy`,type:`M&A`,difficulty:`Moderate`,sector:`Infrastructure`,problem:`Your client is a large EPC company operating on a Build-Operate-Transfer model, building plants and factories for metal processing industries including steel, aluminium, and phosphorous. Growing at 16% per year, the company wants a five-year expansion strategy covering both organic and inorganic options.`,dialogue:[{s:`I`,t:`Your client is a large EPC company on a BOT model building industrial processing plants. Growing at 16% per year. No financial constraints on expansion. Devise a five-year expansion strategy covering organic and inorganic options.`},{s:`C`,t:`I will structure this across two tracks: organic growth through geographic expansion and new sector adjacencies, and inorganic growth through acquisitions. Starting with organic: for geographic expansion within India, which states have the largest pipelines of industrial plant construction in the client's core sectors — steel, aluminium, and mineral processing?`},{s:`I`,t:`Jharkhand, Odisha, and Odisha have the heaviest concentration of mineral reserves and ongoing large plant projects. The client currently has limited presence there.`},{s:`C`,t:`Expanding into Jharkhand and Odisha would require evaluating three factors: first, macro attractiveness — state government investment plans, environmental clearance timelines, and infrastructure quality for large construction projects. Second, operational feasibility — availability of skilled civil and mechanical engineers, local construction material supply chains, and power and water access for construction sites. Third, competitive intensity — how many established EPC players already operate in these geographies, and does the client have a cost or technology advantage. Is the client open to international expansion?`},{s:`I`,t:`Yes, particularly in Southeast Asia and Africa where industrial development is growing.`},{s:`C`,t:`Vietnam, Indonesia, and Ethiopia are attractive targets for EPC expansion in industrial plant construction. Vietnam's manufacturing boom has driven significant demand for factory and processing plant construction. The client's BOT model and Indian cost structure would be competitively attractive in these markets versus European EPC players. On inorganic growth: three acquisition types would be valuable. First, a horizontal acquisition of a mid-sized EPC company in an adjacent geography — either a Jharkhand-based player for immediate local market access, or a Southeast Asian EPC firm. Second, a vertical acquisition — moving upstream to acquire a geological surveying or project management consultancy that can enhance early-stage project origination. Third, a capability acquisition — acquiring an EPC firm specialising in renewable energy plant construction, which is the fastest-growing capital expenditure category in India under the 500 GW renewable target.`},{s:`I`,t:`How would you approach due diligence on a potential acquisition target?`},{s:`C`,t:`For any acquisition candidate I would assess five areas: revenue quality — what proportion of revenue is from long-term contracts versus spot projects, and how concentrated is the customer base. Order book visibility — the next 12-24 months of secured revenue. Key personnel retention — in EPC, the project management and engineering talent is the business; terms preventing departure of top 20 people post-acquisition are essential. Pending litigation and environmental liability — BOT projects in mining and industrial zones carry regulatory risk. And finally, cultural compatibility — EPC execution depends heavily on team coordination; a culture mismatch between the acquirer and target creates delivery risk that can damage the combined firm's reputation.`}]}
];